01:24:29.080 --> 01:24:32.720
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to The Scene and The Unseen, I'm chatting with Srinath Raghavan about

01:24:32.720 --> 01:24:39.760
[Amit Varma]: Kashmir and Article 370 and we've been speaking about Kashmir and Junagadh and Hyderabad and

01:24:39.760 --> 01:24:45.280
[Amit Varma]: Bengal and Sardar Patel and Hindu Nationalists for more than an hour, but finally we have

01:24:45.280 --> 01:24:46.920
[Amit Varma]: got to 370.

01:24:46.920 --> 01:24:52.520
[Amit Varma]: Now tell me if my summation of how 370 kind of came about is broadly correct, so we get

01:24:52.520 --> 01:24:53.980
[Amit Varma]: to the subject.

01:24:53.980 --> 01:24:59.400
[Amit Varma]: In 1947, there was a thing called the Indian Independence Act, which empowered the Governor

01:24:59.400 --> 01:25:04.520
[Amit Varma]: General of India, which was then Lord Mountbatten to adapt the Government of India Act 1935

01:25:04.520 --> 01:25:10.200
[Amit Varma]: as an interim constitution, and then to negotiate with princely states on how they would accede

01:25:10.200 --> 01:25:15.160
[Amit Varma]: to India, which as you pointed out, VP Menon, who was one of the drivers of that working

01:25:15.160 --> 01:25:19.040
[Amit Varma]: with Sardar Patel put together this basic thing that okay, we'll look after defence

01:25:19.040 --> 01:25:23.120
[Amit Varma]: and foreign affairs and communications for you and blah, blah, blah.

01:25:23.120 --> 01:25:29.840
[Amit Varma]: And Kashmir signed an instrument of accession in October 1947, where basically the caveat

01:25:29.840 --> 01:25:34.200
[Amit Varma]: was that this is provisional till the will of the people can be ascertained and Sheikh

01:25:34.200 --> 01:25:40.800
[Amit Varma]: Abdullah was then called to the Constituent Assembly and Article 370 was then formulated

01:25:40.800 --> 01:25:45.160
[Amit Varma]: and though Article 370 as people point out correctly exists since the constitution does

01:25:45.160 --> 01:25:46.240
[Amit Varma]: in 1950.

01:25:46.240 --> 01:25:52.360
[Amit Varma]: It basically formalized what the instrument of accession signed in 1947 already does.

01:25:52.360 --> 01:25:54.200
[Amit Varma]: Is that a correct summation?

01:25:54.200 --> 01:25:56.000
[Guest]: Yes, broadly.

01:25:56.000 --> 01:26:01.680
[Guest]: The only thing I would say is that, you know, when Sheikh Abdullah was and his colleagues

01:26:01.680 --> 01:26:05.640
[Guest]: were asked to sort of join the Indian Constituent Assembly, part of the thing you wanted to

01:26:05.640 --> 01:26:12.080
[Guest]: do was to formalize the relationship of Kashmir with the Union of India and to ensure that

01:26:12.080 --> 01:26:16.640
[Guest]: the Indian Constitution reflected it because what had happened previously was an instrument

01:26:16.640 --> 01:26:21.040
[Guest]: of accession, which had been signed by the Maharaja and, you know, accepted by the Government

01:26:21.040 --> 01:26:24.520
[Guest]: of India, but you wanted to sort of make sure that the Constitution of India as it takes

01:26:24.520 --> 01:26:27.680
[Guest]: shape will reflect this relationship.

01:26:27.680 --> 01:26:34.160
[Guest]: Now the negotiations, which led to ultimately the creation of Article 370, it was actually

01:26:34.160 --> 01:26:40.520
[Guest]: called 306A in the draft of the constitution, basically stretched out over five months because

01:26:40.520 --> 01:26:47.080
[Guest]: what Sheikh Abdullah and his team wanted was to ensure that Kashmir will continue to have

01:26:47.080 --> 01:26:51.440
[Guest]: considerable autonomy because it is only on that condition that he might be able to persuade

01:26:51.440 --> 01:26:55.240
[Guest]: his people that it was better to join India than to join Pakistan.

01:26:55.240 --> 01:26:58.960
[Guest]: And we've already discussed his incentives, all the considerations in front of him.

01:26:58.960 --> 01:27:05.280
[Guest]: So the way in which Article 370 eventually sort of came up was that it says that the

01:27:05.280 --> 01:27:09.240
[Guest]: Government of India is empowered to legislate for the state of Jammu and Kashmir on the

01:27:09.240 --> 01:27:11.400
[Guest]: three subjects of accession.

01:27:11.400 --> 01:27:17.680
[Guest]: If it wants to sort of extend any further provisions of the Indian constitution to that

01:27:17.680 --> 01:27:22.280
[Guest]: state, then Article 370 is the vehicle through which those provisions can be extended to

01:27:22.280 --> 01:27:26.600
[Guest]: the constitution of and made applicable to the state of Jammu and Kashmir.

01:27:26.600 --> 01:27:30.920
[Guest]: But here there are a series of caveats which are built in, which is what safeguard the

01:27:30.920 --> 01:27:32.960
[Guest]: autonomy of the state of Jammu and Kashmir.

01:27:32.960 --> 01:27:37.320
[Guest]: The first caveat is to say that if the President of India issues a presidential order under

01:27:37.320 --> 01:27:41.640
[Guest]: Article 370, you know, extending any provisions which pertain to the three subjects already

01:27:41.640 --> 01:27:47.440
[Guest]: occurred, he only needs the sort of concurrence of the state government, right?

01:27:47.440 --> 01:27:53.800
[Guest]: If he wants to sort of extend any other provisions of the Indian constitution to that state,

01:27:53.800 --> 01:28:01.200
[Guest]: then it will need not just a sort of a straightforward concurrence, but a subsequent approval by

01:28:01.200 --> 01:28:05.200
[Guest]: the constituent assembly of the JNK state itself.

01:28:05.200 --> 01:28:10.920
[Guest]: So in a sense, the ultimate body which decided which other provisions of the Indian constitution

01:28:10.920 --> 01:28:15.360
[Guest]: beyond the three things reflected in the instrument of accession would be applicable to the state

01:28:15.360 --> 01:28:18.780
[Guest]: of JNK would be the state's own constituent assembly.

01:28:18.780 --> 01:28:22.740
[Guest]: It is in that sense that self-determination was offered to the Kashmiris and autonomy

01:28:22.740 --> 01:28:24.440
[Guest]: was guaranteed to them.

01:28:24.440 --> 01:28:29.800
[Guest]: Because the Indian Union could not unilaterally sort of extend provisions using Article 370,

01:28:29.800 --> 01:28:35.280
[Guest]: but you had to get the state's constituent assembly to ratify and accept those provisions.

01:28:35.280 --> 01:28:40.200
[Guest]: And the assumption was that once the state's constituent assembly completed its task of

01:28:40.200 --> 01:28:43.840
[Guest]: making the constitution of the state, it would spell out which of the provisions of the Indian

01:28:43.840 --> 01:28:46.080
[Guest]: constitution it wants to accept.

01:28:46.080 --> 01:28:49.960
[Guest]: And thereafter, no further provisions will be applicable to the state.

01:28:49.960 --> 01:28:54.160
[Guest]: It is in that sense that Article 370 is referred to as temporary provisions for the state of

01:28:54.160 --> 01:28:55.160
[Guest]: JNK.

01:28:55.160 --> 01:29:00.000
[Guest]: The idea was not that you would remove Article 370 and make it permanent, but that the permanent

01:29:00.000 --> 01:29:05.420
[Guest]: contours would only emerge once the state's constituent assembly met, framed the constitution

01:29:05.420 --> 01:29:10.000
[Guest]: of the state and decided what parts of the Indian constitution are we willing to accept.

01:29:10.000 --> 01:29:15.040
[Guest]: So this was the provision for autonomy and a form of sort of self-determination for the

01:29:15.040 --> 01:29:19.740
[Guest]: Kashmiri people, because it was their constituent assembly, which would decide what beyond the

01:29:19.740 --> 01:29:22.840
[Guest]: three subjects they would accept as far as the relationship with India was concerned.

01:29:22.840 --> 01:29:27.040
[Amit Varma]: Right, so to kind of sum it up and tell me if I've done it correctly, again, I'll quote

01:29:27.040 --> 01:29:33.680
[Amit Varma]: Gulzari Nanda, where he talks about 370, where he said in the 60s, quote, the only way of

01:29:33.680 --> 01:29:37.600
[Amit Varma]: taking the constitution of India into Jammu and Kashmir is through the application of

01:29:37.600 --> 01:29:38.600
[Amit Varma]: Article 370.

01:29:38.600 --> 01:29:40.000
[Amit Varma]: It is a tunnel.

01:29:40.000 --> 01:29:45.680
[Amit Varma]: It is through this tunnel that a good deal of traffic has already passed and more will,

01:29:45.680 --> 01:29:46.680
[Amit Varma]: stop quote.

01:29:46.680 --> 01:29:50.720
[Amit Varma]: And as you're pointing out, where India had jurisdiction as far as the state of Jammu

01:29:50.720 --> 01:29:55.560
[Amit Varma]: and Kashmir is concerned is the three subjects of defense, foreign affairs and communication.

01:29:55.560 --> 01:30:00.960
[Amit Varma]: Anything else would need the approval of the state government and the constituent assembly.

01:30:00.960 --> 01:30:05.960
[Amit Varma]: And the constituent assembly, by the time it wound up, which it did deliberately where

01:30:05.960 --> 01:30:11.960
[Amit Varma]: it announced that on so and so a date, I think 1957, 56, you know, by the time it wound up,

01:30:11.960 --> 01:30:16.440
[Amit Varma]: the lines that it would have demarcated would remain forever.

01:30:16.440 --> 01:30:23.800
[Amit Varma]: And also that any change in Article 370 would have to happen with the agreement of the Constituent

01:30:23.800 --> 01:30:28.960
[Amit Varma]: Assembly of J&K, which basically means that by the time it has ceased to exist, no further

01:30:28.960 --> 01:30:30.080
[Amit Varma]: change can happen.

01:30:30.080 --> 01:30:36.720
[Amit Varma]: And Article 370, therefore, is supposed to be sort of permanent at this point in time.

01:30:36.720 --> 01:30:41.740
[Amit Varma]: Now, this is kind of complicated because again, there's a quote I picked up from A. G. Noorani's

01:30:41.740 --> 01:30:48.120
[Amit Varma]: book on Article 370, where he quotes, Nehru is saying that Article 370, quote, has been

01:30:48.120 --> 01:30:53.620
[Amit Varma]: eroded, this is Nehru speaking, has been eroded, if I may use the word, and many things have

01:30:53.620 --> 01:30:57.240
[Amit Varma]: been done in the last few years, which have made the relationship of Kashmir with the

01:30:57.240 --> 01:30:59.280
[Amit Varma]: Union of India very close.

01:30:59.280 --> 01:31:03.780
[Amit Varma]: There is no doubt that Kashmir is fully integrated, stop quote.

01:31:03.780 --> 01:31:08.540
[Amit Varma]: And I was struggling to kind of make sense of this, both in terms of what he meant by

01:31:08.540 --> 01:31:14.060
[Amit Varma]: eroded, and what, you know, defenders of the current move say that Nehru himself through

01:31:14.060 --> 01:31:20.880
[Amit Varma]: a series of presidential orders essentially made 370 almost irrelevant.

01:31:20.880 --> 01:31:25.540
[Amit Varma]: And also, I'm not sure what Nehru meant by Kashmir being fully integrated.

01:31:25.540 --> 01:31:27.060
[Guest]: So the first thing is this, right.

01:31:27.060 --> 01:31:30.080
[Guest]: And that is where I think we need to get to the grips with the history of what happens

01:31:30.080 --> 01:31:33.060
[Guest]: to Article 370 after it is embodied in the Constitution, right?

01:31:33.060 --> 01:31:36.620
[Guest]: Because by the time you come to Gulzarilal Nanda, a lot of water has flowed in the Jhelum

01:31:36.620 --> 01:31:39.220
[Guest]: under the bridges of, you know, JNK.

01:31:39.220 --> 01:31:45.180
[Guest]: Now, Article 370 is adopted as part of the Indian Constitution in 1950, 26th of January

01:31:45.180 --> 01:31:47.780
[Guest]: 1950, the Constitution comes into effect.

01:31:47.780 --> 01:31:54.780
[Guest]: Now, by the end of 1950, the JNK State Constituent Assembly is getting ready to come together

01:31:54.780 --> 01:31:56.840
[Guest]: to form the Constitution of the state.

01:31:56.840 --> 01:32:00.380
[Guest]: And as we know, that is going to be the ultimate body which will decide what provisions of

01:32:00.380 --> 01:32:03.580
[Guest]: the Indian Constitution beyond the three subjects would be acceptable.

01:32:03.580 --> 01:32:09.700
[Guest]: Now even as the JNK State Constituent Assembly starts meeting, Sheikh Abdullah is a little

01:32:09.700 --> 01:32:12.780
[Guest]: impatient to change some aspects of the status quo.

01:32:12.780 --> 01:32:16.860
[Guest]: In particular, he wants to dislodge the Maharaja of Kashmir as the hereditary ruler of the

01:32:16.860 --> 01:32:17.860
[Guest]: state.

01:32:17.860 --> 01:32:19.920
[Guest]: He has a long standing problem with the Maharaja.

01:32:19.920 --> 01:32:25.580
[Guest]: So what he presses upon Nehru is to say that, why don't you issue a presidential order under

01:32:25.580 --> 01:32:32.820
[Guest]: Article 370, effectively saying that the Maharaja's position will be taken over by an elected

01:32:32.820 --> 01:32:40.420
[Guest]: Sadre Riyasat, who will be Maharaja's son, Dr. Karan Singh would take over that position

01:32:40.420 --> 01:32:41.460
[Guest]: and so on.

01:32:41.460 --> 01:32:46.780
[Guest]: It is in that context, actually, that Nehru and Sheikh Abdullah get into a protracted

01:32:46.780 --> 01:32:51.700
[Guest]: correspondence because Nehru says that, you know, the Maharaja of Kashmir is actually

01:32:51.700 --> 01:32:54.480
[Guest]: recognized by the President of India in the Indian Constitution.

01:32:54.480 --> 01:32:59.660
[Guest]: So if you want to do away with him, then we have to at least broadly decide what the contours

01:32:59.660 --> 01:33:06.020
[Guest]: of the relationship between India and Srinagar should be, or, you know, between New Delhi

01:33:06.020 --> 01:33:09.860
[Guest]: and Srinagar should be, which actually is a task which is left to the Constituent Assembly.

01:33:09.860 --> 01:33:13.180
[Guest]: But he says, we must accept some guidelines, which is then your responsibility to make

01:33:13.180 --> 01:33:17.960
[Guest]: sure the Constituent Assembly fleshes it out and gives effects to that understanding.

01:33:17.960 --> 01:33:21.980
[Guest]: Because you are asking for changes even before the Constituent Assembly has started its business.

01:33:21.980 --> 01:33:26.100
[Guest]: So if we have to, if we want to, I can't do this piecemeal because this will have implications

01:33:26.100 --> 01:33:27.100
[Guest]: constitutionally.

01:33:27.100 --> 01:33:29.520
[Guest]: So we have to do a few other things.

01:33:29.520 --> 01:33:33.540
[Guest]: So it is in that context that as part of negotiations between the two sides, they come to something

01:33:33.540 --> 01:33:40.100
[Guest]: called a Delhi Agreement of 1952, whereby the two sides try and align their positions

01:33:40.100 --> 01:33:45.460
[Guest]: on what the autonomy of JNK will mean as far as accepting various provisions of the Indian

01:33:45.460 --> 01:33:46.460
[Guest]: Constitution or not.

01:33:46.460 --> 01:33:49.540
[Guest]: They don't get into very great detail, but they say what are broadly the kinds of things

01:33:49.540 --> 01:33:50.540
[Guest]: that will be acceptable, right?

01:33:50.540 --> 01:33:54.500
[Guest]: Like, so for instance, you know, the idea that JNK state will have its own flag, you

01:33:54.500 --> 01:33:57.460
[Guest]: know, it is going to have, you know, various kinds of things, right?

01:33:57.460 --> 01:34:00.740
[Guest]: So that is what the 1952 agreement really is about.

01:34:00.740 --> 01:34:07.700
[Guest]: And the 1952 agreement, at least as far as Jawaharlal Nehru is concerned, enables a synchronization

01:34:07.700 --> 01:34:12.540
[Guest]: of the constitutions of India and the future constitution of JNK.

01:34:12.540 --> 01:34:16.500
[Guest]: It lays down certain markers that both sides will agree when they are thinking about this

01:34:16.500 --> 01:34:18.660
[Guest]: relationship, right?

01:34:18.660 --> 01:34:21.300
[Guest]: But Sheikh Abdullah has two problems.

01:34:21.300 --> 01:34:25.380
[Guest]: First, the agreement actually does not go down all that well in Srinagar.

01:34:25.380 --> 01:34:30.540
[Guest]: Because people believe that Sheikh Abdullah has somewhat preemptively undermined the autonomous

01:34:30.540 --> 01:34:33.020
[Guest]: authority of the Constituent Assembly of JNK.

01:34:33.020 --> 01:34:36.680
[Guest]: And that he has somehow sort of, you know, indulged in a bit of a sell off to this thing.

01:34:36.680 --> 01:34:39.420
[Guest]: And this is against the context when plebiscite is still a possibility, many other things

01:34:39.420 --> 01:34:40.420
[Guest]: are in the air, right?

01:34:40.420 --> 01:34:42.740
[Guest]: UN is still hotly debating this issue.

01:34:42.740 --> 01:34:44.020
[Guest]: So that's the problem.

01:34:44.020 --> 01:34:49.460
[Guest]: The second problem for Sheikh Abdullah is that the Janasang and Shama Prasad Mukherjee

01:34:49.460 --> 01:34:52.620
[Guest]: take the Delhi agreement as a major target.

01:34:52.620 --> 01:34:58.940
[Guest]: But in order to this, right, and the slogan of the time was that, ek desh mein doh vidhan,

01:34:58.940 --> 01:35:01.340
[Guest]: doh nishan, doh pradhan, right?

01:35:01.340 --> 01:35:07.820
[Guest]: Two constitutions, two flags, and two sort of rulers, Sadr-e-Riyasat as well as the president

01:35:07.820 --> 01:35:08.820
[Guest]: should not be.

01:35:08.820 --> 01:35:09.820
[Guest]: Nahi chalega, nahi chalega.

01:35:09.820 --> 01:35:10.820
[Guest]: Right?

01:35:10.820 --> 01:35:11.820
[Guest]: That was the thing.

01:35:11.820 --> 01:35:14.140
[Guest]: So they really targeted the 1952 accord.

01:35:14.140 --> 01:35:19.500
[Guest]: And Sheikh Abdullah thereafter became very, very worried about whether India will actually

01:35:19.500 --> 01:35:23.020
[Guest]: be able to sort of guarantee Kashmir's autonomy in perpetuity.

01:35:23.020 --> 01:35:26.260
[Guest]: Or are these forces of the Hindu right really going to come?

01:35:26.260 --> 01:35:29.260
[Guest]: And it's in that context that you know, actually Jawaharlal Nehru writes letters and makes

01:35:29.260 --> 01:35:30.260
[Guest]: speeches.

01:35:30.260 --> 01:35:34.580
[Guest]: He says, why should the Kashmiris be part of India, if the Janasang and RSS are going

01:35:34.580 --> 01:35:36.300
[Guest]: to be in the driver's seat?

01:35:36.300 --> 01:35:38.700
[Guest]: Because they know very well that these guys are going to erode any autonomy that is left

01:35:38.700 --> 01:35:39.700
[Amit Varma]: there.

01:35:39.700 --> 01:35:40.700
[Amit Varma]: Right?

01:35:40.700 --> 01:35:43.500
[Amit Varma]: And the Hindu right is not just from India, it's also the Praja Parishad in Jammu, like

01:35:43.500 --> 01:35:45.660
[Guest]: you pointed out, which is doing a lot of stuff there.

01:35:45.660 --> 01:35:50.460
[Guest]: By now, they have been sort of co-opted into this thing, right? and there are other elements

01:35:50.460 --> 01:35:55.700
[Guest]: like the Sadr Ariyasat himself, who's a former ruler's son, Dr. Karan Singh, who has conflicted

01:35:55.700 --> 01:35:56.700
[Guest]: views about various things.

01:35:56.700 --> 01:35:57.700
[Guest]: Right?

01:35:57.700 --> 01:36:00.980
[Guest]: I mean, he presents everything as if the people of Jammu have different aspirations that are

01:36:00.980 --> 01:36:01.980
[Guest]: different.

01:36:01.980 --> 01:36:03.460
[Guest]: But he's also a factor in this game.

01:36:03.460 --> 01:36:08.300
[Guest]: And there is a third factor, which is a group of influential sort of Kashmiri pandits, who

01:36:08.300 --> 01:36:13.020
[Guest]: are associates of Sheikh Abdullah, but eventually then start doubting Sheikh Abdullah's own

01:36:13.020 --> 01:36:14.020
[Guest]: motives.

01:36:14.020 --> 01:36:19.100
[Guest]: There is a man who would later became a very influential player in under Mrs. Indira Gandhi

01:36:19.100 --> 01:36:20.100
[Guest]: called D.P.

01:36:20.100 --> 01:36:21.100
[Guest]: Dhar.

01:36:21.100 --> 01:36:22.100
[Guest]: D.P.

01:36:22.100 --> 01:36:24.100
[Amit Varma]: Dhar became India's ambassador to the Soviet Union during the 1971 crisis.

01:36:24.100 --> 01:36:26.100
[Amit Varma]: Entirely discussed him in our Bangladesh episode.

01:36:26.100 --> 01:36:27.100
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

01:36:27.100 --> 01:36:28.100
[Guest]: So everything comes together.

01:36:28.100 --> 01:36:32.020
[Guest]: You can see how some of these characters have never let go of me for the last 15 years.

01:36:32.020 --> 01:36:33.020
[Guest]: Right?

01:36:33.020 --> 01:36:34.020
[Guest]: So D.P.

01:36:34.020 --> 01:36:35.020
[Guest]: Dhar was one of those people.

01:36:35.020 --> 01:36:43.580
[Guest]: And it is this group of people, which is the Sadr Ariyasat Karan Singh, some of Sheikh Abdullah's

01:36:43.580 --> 01:36:47.460
[Guest]: own associates, including others, and this is not a Hindu Muslim thing, right?

01:36:47.460 --> 01:36:49.460
[Guest]: I mean, there are some like D.P.

01:36:49.460 --> 01:36:53.780
[Guest]: Dhar, but there are others like, you know, Bakshri Ghulam Muhammad, who is effectively

01:36:53.780 --> 01:36:58.260
[Guest]: number two, who believe that the line that Abdullah is now sort of treading, which is

01:36:58.260 --> 01:37:02.860
[Guest]: to say, listen, let's look for some kind of a different status for Kashmir, which we discussed,

01:37:02.860 --> 01:37:03.860
[Guest]: right?

01:37:03.860 --> 01:37:07.020
[Guest]: He wanted some kind of an agreement between India and Pakistan, guaranteeing some kind

01:37:07.020 --> 01:37:10.860
[Guest]: of independent status for Kashmir, etc, etc, was the wrong thing to do.

01:37:10.860 --> 01:37:11.860
[Guest]: Right?

01:37:11.860 --> 01:37:14.580
[Guest]: And Abdullah, of course, is reacting to these two things.

01:37:14.580 --> 01:37:18.980
[Guest]: One to the unpopularity of the Delhi Agreement within his own thing, second to the attack

01:37:18.980 --> 01:37:24.380
[Guest]: on the Delhi Agreement being mounted by the Janasangh and others sort of, you know, approving

01:37:24.380 --> 01:37:25.380
[Guest]: of that.

01:37:25.380 --> 01:37:29.020
[Guest]: And then, of course, Shama Prasad Mukherjee dies in a sort of a jail in Srinagar.

01:37:29.020 --> 01:37:30.020
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:37:30.020 --> 01:37:32.860
[Guest]: Post all of that, Sheikh Abdullah then becomes very nervous and starts making all of these

01:37:32.860 --> 01:37:33.860
[Guest]: different kinds of moves.

01:37:33.860 --> 01:37:38.300
[Guest]: He starts meeting the American ambassador, Nehru through his intelligence agencies, gets

01:37:38.300 --> 01:37:42.220
[Guest]: to know influential people like Karan Singh and D.P.

01:37:42.220 --> 01:37:46.940
[Guest]: Dhar and Bakshi Ghulam Muhammad are plotting behind the scenes to prepare the way for Sheikh

01:37:46.940 --> 01:37:48.620
[Guest]: Abdullah's departure.

01:37:48.620 --> 01:37:52.060
[Guest]: They convinced Jawaharlal Nehru that Abdullah has to be gotten rid of.

01:37:52.060 --> 01:37:57.340
[Guest]: Yeah, there is actually a very, very interesting letter, which I found much later in the archives

01:37:57.340 --> 01:37:58.340
[Guest]: of P.N.

01:37:58.340 --> 01:38:00.820
[Guest]: Haksar, who was Mrs. Gandhi's principal secretary.

01:38:00.820 --> 01:38:01.820
[Guest]: Another Bangladesh protagonist.

01:38:01.820 --> 01:38:03.860
[Guest]: Another Bangladesh protagonist.

01:38:03.860 --> 01:38:04.860
[Guest]: This is from 1972.

01:38:04.860 --> 01:38:05.860
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:38:05.860 --> 01:38:10.820
[Guest]: This is in the context of what later became the Simla Accords and stuff.

01:38:10.820 --> 01:38:14.820
[Guest]: And Haksar at that point of time is a great advocate of some kind of rapprochement with

01:38:14.820 --> 01:38:15.820
[Guest]: Sheikh Abdullah.

01:38:15.820 --> 01:38:18.940
[Guest]: You know, this is, we're talking about 20 years fast forwarding.

01:38:18.940 --> 01:38:21.820
[Guest]: And he says that, I met D.P.

01:38:21.820 --> 01:38:26.180
[Guest]: Dhar the other day, and I told him that since he was responsible for the original sin in

01:38:26.180 --> 01:38:30.140
[Guest]: Kashmir, maybe he should take the first step to reach out to Sheikh Abdullah.

01:38:30.140 --> 01:38:33.860
[Guest]: And the original sin was the imprisonment and arbitrary dismissal of Sheikh Abdullah

01:38:33.860 --> 01:38:41.900
[Guest]: in 1953, which frankly was one of those things which led to a, which created a rupture in

01:38:41.900 --> 01:38:46.580
[Guest]: the minds of the Muslims of Kashmir valley in particular, because it was seen by them

01:38:46.580 --> 01:38:51.260
[Guest]: and remains, continues to be seen by them as an enormous historical betrayal of India's

01:38:51.260 --> 01:38:55.620
[Guest]: promise of autonomy to Kashmir because their tallest leader, the person who was sort of

01:38:55.620 --> 01:39:00.420
[Guest]: negotiating was arbitrarily removed, arrested and put in prison.

01:39:00.420 --> 01:39:03.100
[Guest]: Subsequently various kinds of charges were foisted on him, none of which were sort of

01:39:03.100 --> 01:39:06.860
[Guest]: proven in a court of law, but he remained in and out of prisons for a very, very long

01:39:06.860 --> 01:39:07.860
[Guest]: period of time.

01:39:07.860 --> 01:39:12.700
[Guest]: And I think that sort of ruptured and Nehru himself knew that he was taking a very dangerous

01:39:12.700 --> 01:39:20.620
[Guest]: move in sort of dismissing Sheikh Abdullah, but he, against his better judgment allowed

01:39:20.620 --> 01:39:23.260
[Guest]: himself to sort of go ahead and do that.

01:39:23.260 --> 01:39:26.300
[Guest]: And he was instrumental in that, even though he kept insisting that it was done by the

01:39:26.300 --> 01:39:29.180
[Guest]: people on the ground, but historical records suggest otherwise.

01:39:29.180 --> 01:39:34.260
[Guest]: Sheikh Lala Nehru was totally in sync with this plan to remove Sheikh Abdullah.

01:39:34.260 --> 01:39:38.540
[Guest]: In fact, he dictates a note to his secretary, Emma Mothai, saying, what are the various

01:39:38.540 --> 01:39:42.020
[Guest]: steps which have to be taken to ensure that public order is maintained after Abdullah

01:39:42.020 --> 01:39:43.020
[Guest]: is removed?

01:39:43.020 --> 01:39:44.020
[Guest]: How does he justify it to himself?

01:39:44.020 --> 01:39:45.020
[Guest]: Realpolitik, I suppose, right?

01:39:45.020 --> 01:39:50.980
[Guest]: I mean, see, when you are in these positions of power, you have certain kinds of principles,

01:39:50.980 --> 01:39:55.060
[Guest]: you have this extraordinary friendship with Sheikh Abdullah, you know, various things,

01:39:55.060 --> 01:39:58.300
[Guest]: but you just feel like, listen, if I don't act at this point of time in this way, then

01:39:58.300 --> 01:40:00.220
[Guest]: maybe the state is going to get out of my control.

01:40:00.220 --> 01:40:05.480
[Guest]: And I who have been a great champion and votary of Kashmir being a symbol of India secularism

01:40:05.480 --> 01:40:10.740
[Guest]: will then have failed in not just persuading my countrymen to accept it, but in keeping

01:40:10.740 --> 01:40:11.740
[Guest]: them in our fold.

01:40:11.740 --> 01:40:12.740
[Guest]: Right?

01:40:12.740 --> 01:40:15.780
[Guest]: So it's one of those ruthless realpolitik decisions which is taken.

01:40:15.780 --> 01:40:20.980
[Guest]: And I think it looks at least as bad in retrospect as it did in prospect.

01:40:20.980 --> 01:40:25.660
[Guest]: And I think history has vindicated it to be the single most grievous error made by India

01:40:25.660 --> 01:40:27.500
[Guest]: in its dealings with JNK.

01:40:27.500 --> 01:40:32.460
[Guest]: I think everything else could have sort of possibly worked out in India's favor, had

01:40:32.460 --> 01:40:38.140
[Guest]: this move to depose Sheikh Abdullah in such an arbitrary and, you know, unlawful illegal

01:40:38.140 --> 01:40:40.260
[Guest]: manner not been taken.

01:40:40.260 --> 01:40:43.340
[Guest]: And it's also worth pointing out that immediately after the arrest of Sheikh Abdullah, there

01:40:43.340 --> 01:40:45.100
[Guest]: were popular protests in Kashmir.

01:40:45.100 --> 01:40:49.140
[Guest]: And many people were shot and killed in putting down those protests.

01:40:49.140 --> 01:40:52.100
[Guest]: It is again because of a news blackout is not something that is reported in mainstream

01:40:52.100 --> 01:40:54.660
[Guest]: newspapers of the time, but it's well known.

01:40:54.660 --> 01:40:58.260
[Amit Varma]: So what, what were the repercussions of this, like, I don't want to bother you with another

01:40:58.260 --> 01:41:02.460
[Amit Varma]: complex counterfactual, but just a sort of a simpler counterfactual question that if

01:41:02.460 --> 01:41:05.460
[Amit Varma]: Nehru hadn't done this, what would the best case scenario have been?

01:41:05.460 --> 01:41:08.900
[Guest]: Well, the best case scenario would have been to sort of try and persuade Sheikh Abdullah

01:41:08.900 --> 01:41:14.700
[Guest]: to sort of, you know, come up with some other kind of an arrangement which would allow him

01:41:14.700 --> 01:41:17.700
[Guest]: to sell autonomy to his own people in a strong way.

01:41:17.700 --> 01:41:18.700
[Guest]: Because what was Abdullah's problem?

01:41:18.700 --> 01:41:23.940
[Guest]: Abdullah's problem was that he believed that in the wake of the rise of the Dhansangh and

01:41:23.940 --> 01:41:27.620
[Guest]: these kinds of protests, and you know, they had various kinds of rallies, marches, especially

01:41:27.620 --> 01:41:28.620
[Guest]: all of North India.

01:41:28.620 --> 01:41:29.620
[Guest]: Right.

01:41:29.620 --> 01:41:32.100
[Guest]: He just felt like, you know, it is going to be impossible for me to convince Kashmiri

01:41:32.100 --> 01:41:35.980
[Guest]: Muslims that their future in an autonomous fashion is somehow safe in an India of the

01:41:35.980 --> 01:41:36.980
[Guest]: sky.

01:41:36.980 --> 01:41:38.900
[Guest]: So in a sense, it would have taken a lot.

01:41:38.900 --> 01:41:41.260
[Guest]: And maybe Jawaharlal Nehru would have also had to think out creatively.

01:41:41.260 --> 01:41:49.140
[Guest]: And again, he did in 1964 on the sort of on literally on his deathbed, Jawaharlal Nehru

01:41:49.140 --> 01:41:53.340
[Guest]: attempted to sort of reach out to Sheikh Abdullah, even sent Sheikh Abdullah to Pakistan to say,

01:41:53.340 --> 01:41:55.060
[Guest]: you try and explore some settlement, right?

01:41:55.060 --> 01:42:00.340
[Guest]: Because by that time, 11 years after that act of 1953, Jawaharlal Nehru was living to

01:42:00.340 --> 01:42:01.740
[Guest]: review the day.

01:42:01.740 --> 01:42:07.180
[Guest]: Because in essence, what he realized by the time he died was that the Kashmir issue, far

01:42:07.180 --> 01:42:13.260
[Guest]: from securing India's secularism, had actually created a huge weapon for Hindu majoritarianism

01:42:13.260 --> 01:42:17.500
[Guest]: in this country, because that state's special status could be turned as a weapon against

01:42:17.500 --> 01:42:19.740
[Guest]: Muslims, which is exactly what was happening.

01:42:19.740 --> 01:42:24.260
[Guest]: Jawaharlal Nehru lived to see the consequences of this, realized that at least if in my lifetime,

01:42:24.260 --> 01:42:28.100
[Guest]: I do not make one attempt, it is not very clear what he could have done at that point

01:42:28.100 --> 01:42:29.100
[Guest]: of time.

01:42:29.100 --> 01:42:31.700
[Guest]: He was old, weak, ailing.

01:42:31.700 --> 01:42:34.300
[Guest]: And it is not very clear that anything would have come out of that.

01:42:34.300 --> 01:42:38.740
[Guest]: But the mere fact that he did it, I think, was the best gesture of repentance that he

01:42:38.740 --> 01:42:42.500
[Guest]: could have bought himself to do, which was to sort of reach out to a man whom he had

01:42:42.500 --> 01:42:47.380
[Guest]: imprisoned and said that, listen, you go to Pakistan, you try what can be tried.

01:42:47.380 --> 01:42:51.360
[Guest]: In fact, that episode is very well covered in Ramachandra Guha's book, India after Gandhi.

01:42:51.360 --> 01:42:56.420
[Guest]: But I think, you know, it came too little too late in the day.

01:42:56.420 --> 01:43:00.180
[Amit Varma]: So the, you know, what Nehru did, the one of the political repercussions of that, of

01:43:00.180 --> 01:43:03.500
[Amit Varma]: course, which we are feeling to the present day is that it became one of the central causes

01:43:03.500 --> 01:43:06.200
[Amit Varma]: for the Hindutva right.

01:43:06.200 --> 01:43:09.660
[Amit Varma]: What were the repercussions of it for Kashmir and for Kashmiris?

01:43:09.660 --> 01:43:12.520
[Guest]: Well, the important repercussions and that is the point, right?

01:43:12.520 --> 01:43:17.400
[Guest]: It is after Sheikh Abdullah's dismissal that Article 370, rather than becoming the guarantee

01:43:17.400 --> 01:43:22.620
[Guest]: of Kashmir's autonomy, becomes the instrument through which the will of the central government

01:43:22.620 --> 01:43:24.920
[Guest]: is arbitrarily imposed on the state.

01:43:24.920 --> 01:43:30.540
[Guest]: Because the first important, big, you know, mega presidential order is given as early

01:43:30.540 --> 01:43:31.540
[Guest]: as 1954.

01:43:31.540 --> 01:43:34.900
[Guest]: Now, you could say that, you know, the Kashmir Constituent Assembly is still meeting at that

01:43:34.900 --> 01:43:35.900
[Guest]: point of time.

01:43:35.900 --> 01:43:39.540
[Guest]: So maybe exporting all those provisions was something that they agreed the Kashmir Constituent

01:43:39.540 --> 01:43:40.820
[Guest]: Assembly ratified it.

01:43:40.820 --> 01:43:47.740
[Guest]: Yeah, so you can say that at least that notion of the letter of the law was at least followed.

01:43:47.740 --> 01:43:55.020
[Guest]: But post the meeting, dissolution, promulgation of the constitution of JNK, there is no way

01:43:55.020 --> 01:43:59.420
[Guest]: that further provisions of the Indian constitution could be imported to the state under Article

01:43:59.420 --> 01:44:00.420
[Guest]: 370.

01:44:00.420 --> 01:44:02.500
[Guest]: But that is exactly what was done.

01:44:02.500 --> 01:44:06.180
[Guest]: And that is what Jawaharlal Nehru is referring to when he says that more and more things

01:44:06.180 --> 01:44:08.380
[Guest]: have been done to integrate the state closer with India.

01:44:08.380 --> 01:44:11.060
[Amit Varma]: And he uses the word eroded repeatedly.

01:44:11.060 --> 01:44:15.300
[Guest]: It is better in the actual parliamentary debate, because he said it in Hindi.

01:44:15.300 --> 01:44:18.160
[Guest]: He said, ye ghiste ghiste ghis jayega.

01:44:18.160 --> 01:44:19.820
[Guest]: Then why is it still an issue?

01:44:19.820 --> 01:44:24.420
[Guest]: It is only an issue because it became an ideological issue for the Janasan and subsequently for

01:44:24.420 --> 01:44:25.640
[Guest]: the BJP.

01:44:25.640 --> 01:44:32.580
[Guest]: Because the reality is that as of 5th August 2019, when Article 370 was totally hollowed

01:44:32.580 --> 01:44:34.860
[Guest]: out, it is still on the papers of the constitution, right?

01:44:34.860 --> 01:44:38.220
[Guest]: It's not gone because taking it out would have other repercussions.

01:44:38.220 --> 01:44:40.180
[Guest]: But it was a dead letter.

01:44:40.180 --> 01:44:44.180
[Guest]: You could do things to that state through Article 370, which you could not do to any

01:44:44.180 --> 01:44:45.220
[Guest]: other state of India.

01:44:45.220 --> 01:44:48.380
[Guest]: Like imposing president's rule for a very long period between 1990 and 1996 through

01:44:48.380 --> 01:44:51.060
[Guest]: a series of presidential orders, we kept imposing.

01:44:51.060 --> 01:44:53.820
[Guest]: You try imposing president rule on any other thing, you need to amend the Indian constitution

01:44:53.820 --> 01:44:54.820
[Guest]: to do that.

01:44:54.820 --> 01:44:55.860
[Guest]: You don't need to do that with JNK.

01:44:55.860 --> 01:45:00.460
[Guest]: So far from being the protector, the shield which protect the economy, it became as Gulzari

01:45:00.460 --> 01:45:04.980
[Guest]: Lal Nanda said, a tunnel through which everything could be done to that state, irrespective

01:45:04.980 --> 01:45:09.300
[Guest]: of what the wishes of the people were, well, well after the Constituent Assembly of that

01:45:09.300 --> 01:45:11.380
[Amit Varma]: state had dissolved.

01:45:11.380 --> 01:45:17.340
[Amit Varma]: So what was done on August 5, therefore, is really something which is big for the Hindutva,

01:45:17.340 --> 01:45:18.340
[Amit Varma]: right?

01:45:18.340 --> 01:45:21.780
[Amit Varma]: Because of his symbolic value in practical terms, it doesn't really make a difference.

01:45:21.780 --> 01:45:25.620
[Amit Varma]: India can still do whatever the India could still was still doing whatever the hell it

01:45:25.620 --> 01:45:26.620
[Guest]: wanted there.

01:45:26.620 --> 01:45:28.060
[Guest]: There are two things, right?

01:45:28.060 --> 01:45:33.740
[Guest]: So one is, yes, it is true that India was doing whatever, you know, in a sense, all

01:45:33.740 --> 01:45:39.860
[Guest]: kinds of provisions of the Indian constitution were being extended to that state on the name

01:45:39.860 --> 01:45:40.860
[Guest]: of this thing.

01:45:40.860 --> 01:45:41.860
[Guest]: Right.

01:45:41.860 --> 01:45:46.300
[Guest]: And the sad bit is that the Indian Supreme Court never took an unequivocal stand on this

01:45:46.300 --> 01:45:47.300
[Guest]: issue.

01:45:47.300 --> 01:45:50.500
[Guest]: There is one important ruling where they said that the Constituent Assembly should be the

01:45:50.500 --> 01:45:51.500
[Guest]: ultimate ratifying authority.

01:45:51.500 --> 01:45:55.540
[Guest]: There is another ruling in which they have said that, you know, maybe the state legislature

01:45:55.540 --> 01:45:56.540
[Guest]: can support it.

01:45:56.540 --> 01:45:59.380
[Guest]: But what today is happening is that we are being told that the governor can stand in

01:45:59.380 --> 01:46:00.380
[Guest]: even for the state legislature.

01:46:00.380 --> 01:46:05.380
[Guest]: You're taking the reductio ad absurdum of that argument that a Constituent Assembly,

01:46:05.380 --> 01:46:10.060
[Guest]: which is a sovereign body, which has in any scheme of politics, greater powers than a

01:46:10.060 --> 01:46:15.140
[Guest]: normal elected legislative assembly today can be said to be equivalent to the governor

01:46:15.140 --> 01:46:17.020
[Guest]: of a state which is under President's rule.

01:46:17.020 --> 01:46:20.140
[Guest]: Now, that is the extent to which these things have been done.

01:46:20.140 --> 01:46:23.940
[Guest]: The second thing which has been of course done under the current move is the reduction

01:46:23.940 --> 01:46:26.780
[Guest]: of the state to a union territory status, which is a very different thing.

01:46:26.780 --> 01:46:28.180
[Guest]: I think we should come to that in a bit.

01:46:28.180 --> 01:46:29.180
[Amit Varma]: We'll come to that.

01:46:29.180 --> 01:46:35.700
[Amit Varma]: You know, I'll link to Gautam Bhatia's excellent piece on exactly how the government did the

01:46:35.700 --> 01:46:40.900
[Amit Varma]: constitutional higgery-jiggery-pokery by which it sort of did what it did.

01:46:40.900 --> 01:46:43.780
[Guest]: But can you briefly summarize what exactly it did?

01:46:43.780 --> 01:46:48.340
[Guest]: So the main stumbling block for the government was this provision within Article 370 that

01:46:48.340 --> 01:46:52.820
[Guest]: the extension of any other provisions of the Indian Constitution would have to be ratified

01:46:52.820 --> 01:46:54.780
[Guest]: by the state's Constituent Assembly.

01:46:54.780 --> 01:47:00.180
[Guest]: So what the presidential order which was issued on 5th of August attempts to do is to circumvent

01:47:00.180 --> 01:47:01.620
[Guest]: that through a backdoor.

01:47:01.620 --> 01:47:05.260
[Guest]: They have said that we will amend Article 367, which is the explanations clause of the

01:47:05.260 --> 01:47:12.940
[Guest]: article, to say that for state Constituent Assembly, read state government as advised

01:47:12.940 --> 01:47:14.300
[Guest]: by so and so.

01:47:14.300 --> 01:47:17.700
[Guest]: And they have made a claim that currently there is no state government there and that

01:47:17.700 --> 01:47:19.060
[Guest]: the governor stands in for that.

01:47:19.060 --> 01:47:20.060
[Guest]: Right.

01:47:20.060 --> 01:47:24.680
[Guest]: So it's a backdoor through which now the problem with that, as Gautam points out in his piece,

01:47:24.680 --> 01:47:29.060
[Guest]: is that in effect, what they have done is they have used Article 370 to amend Article

01:47:29.060 --> 01:47:31.940
[Guest]: 370 itself, which is highly problematic.

01:47:31.940 --> 01:47:35.420
[Guest]: You cannot use any of the provisions of the Constitution to amend itself.

01:47:35.420 --> 01:47:37.940
[Guest]: You have to invoke the amendment powers of the Constitution.

01:47:37.940 --> 01:47:42.940
[Amit Varma]: Remind me to ask you about Sikkim in 1975, which is a very, I think that's a total rabbit

01:47:42.940 --> 01:47:43.940
[Guest]: hole.

01:47:43.940 --> 01:47:46.340
[Guest]: Anyway, so, so that is the first thing, right?

01:47:46.340 --> 01:47:50.020
[Guest]: So they've done things in an indirect way.

01:47:50.020 --> 01:47:54.660
[Guest]: But that is likely to raise a series of constitutional sort of questions, which the courts will have

01:47:54.660 --> 01:47:57.420
[Guest]: to sort of decide on whether that is happening.

01:47:57.420 --> 01:48:03.140
[Guest]: There is a second problem vis-a-vis how they have sort of gone about doing this, right,

01:48:03.140 --> 01:48:07.700
[Guest]: which is to say that the first presidential order that was issued that way, the same day,

01:48:07.700 --> 01:48:12.220
[Guest]: the Home Minister tabled another presidential order to get the Parliament's approval, which

01:48:12.220 --> 01:48:17.980
[Guest]: basically said that from here on, every other article barring Article, you know, Clause

01:48:17.980 --> 01:48:21.060
[Guest]: 1 of 370 stands is to be taken away.

01:48:21.060 --> 01:48:25.180
[Guest]: Clause 1 will now say that every article of the Indian Constitution, irrespective of anything

01:48:25.180 --> 01:48:27.220
[Guest]: ever done will apply, right?

01:48:27.220 --> 01:48:31.900
[Guest]: So it's a dramatic wholesale change of Article 370 itself.

01:48:31.900 --> 01:48:38.860
[Guest]: Now that falls into another problem because the original Article 370 states specifically

01:48:38.860 --> 01:48:44.540
[Guest]: that Article 1 of the Indian Constitution and Article 370 applied to the state of Jammu

01:48:44.540 --> 01:48:45.820
[Guest]: and Kashmir.

01:48:45.820 --> 01:48:50.000
[Guest]: If any other provisions of the Constitution have to be applied, then you can use a presidential

01:48:50.000 --> 01:48:55.180
[Guest]: order, which only means to say that you cannot extend Article 370 to that state again in

01:48:55.180 --> 01:48:57.580
[Guest]: a new form through a presidential order.

01:48:57.580 --> 01:49:01.540
[Guest]: Now, this is the reason why it took five months to draft that article.

01:49:01.540 --> 01:49:05.620
[Guest]: It is not as if these kind of ideas have been come up with a bunch of geniuses or that could

01:49:05.620 --> 01:49:07.660
[Guest]: not have been anticipated at that time.

01:49:07.660 --> 01:49:10.800
[Guest]: It is very easily foreseeable that a group of people could have destroyed the autonomy

01:49:10.800 --> 01:49:15.660
[Guest]: of the state using Article 370 if these safeguards were not in place, which is why Sheikh Abdullah

01:49:15.660 --> 01:49:20.020
[Guest]: negotiated for five months and bought all of these provisions in.

01:49:20.020 --> 01:49:24.900
[Guest]: And despite that, NG Iyengar has explained all of these provisions in his sort of speech

01:49:24.900 --> 01:49:28.300
[Guest]: in the Constituent Assembly where he tables the article to say this is the provision.

01:49:28.300 --> 01:49:31.420
[Guest]: These are the reasons why we are doing all of these things, right?

01:49:31.420 --> 01:49:36.620
[Guest]: So in effect, I think, therefore, this raises a whole series of sort of constitutional questions

01:49:36.620 --> 01:49:41.900
[Guest]: about the legality of an order like this, which the courts will have to sit on and decide

01:49:41.900 --> 01:49:42.900
[Guest]: and deliberate.

01:49:42.900 --> 01:49:46.320
[Guest]: But I think there's one more thing which is worth wearing out.

01:49:46.320 --> 01:49:49.500
[Guest]: What is the overall consequence of what has been done?

01:49:49.500 --> 01:49:55.140
[Guest]: The overall consequence of what has been done is to nullify the constitution of the state

01:49:55.140 --> 01:49:57.860
[Guest]: of Jammu and Kashmir.

01:49:57.860 --> 01:50:05.260
[Guest]: The position and legitimacy of that constitution was enshrined in the Indian constitution through

01:50:05.260 --> 01:50:07.760
[Guest]: Article 370.

01:50:07.760 --> 01:50:12.060
[Guest]: It was a provision of the Indian constitution to accept that state's constitution.

01:50:12.060 --> 01:50:16.940
[Guest]: Now in effect, we have destroyed that state's constitution wholesale.

01:50:16.940 --> 01:50:21.260
[Guest]: Now what does that mean for the basic structure of the constitution, etc., I think is another

01:50:21.260 --> 01:50:26.180
[Guest]: issue that constitutional lawyers and the courts will be deliberating in the weeks and

01:50:26.180 --> 01:50:27.180
[Amit Varma]: months to come.

01:50:27.180 --> 01:50:29.780
[Amit Varma]: What does it mean for Indian federalism?

01:50:29.780 --> 01:50:34.100
[Guest]: I think that is where the second part of the whole thing becomes much more difficult, right?

01:50:34.100 --> 01:50:37.880
[Guest]: There are two aspects of this question of federalism, which I think we need to deliberate.

01:50:37.880 --> 01:50:42.980
[Guest]: One relates to 370 itself, and the second relates to the union territorial sort of creation

01:50:42.980 --> 01:50:46.420
[Guest]: of two union territories in what was a Nerstwile state.

01:50:46.420 --> 01:50:49.220
[Guest]: Now let's look at 370 itself first.

01:50:49.220 --> 01:50:53.740
[Guest]: 370 is not the only part of the Indian constitution which has such asymmetric provisions.

01:50:53.740 --> 01:50:56.780
[Guest]: If you read Article 370, and there are many other states which have various kinds of asymmetric

01:50:56.780 --> 01:51:00.220
[Guest]: provisions, nor is J&K the only state where you cannot purchase land.

01:51:00.220 --> 01:51:03.540
[Guest]: There are many other states which have similar provisions, particularly with respect to agricultural

01:51:03.540 --> 01:51:04.540
[Guest]: land.

01:51:04.540 --> 01:51:08.060
[Guest]: There are many kinds of ceilings and restrictions about what non-domiciles can and cannot do

01:51:08.060 --> 01:51:09.220
[Guest]: in states, right?

01:51:09.220 --> 01:51:12.020
[Guest]: These are all parts of the federal provisions of the constitution.

01:51:12.020 --> 01:51:17.340
[Guest]: So asymmetric constitutional provisions was a fundamental part of the design of the Indian

01:51:17.340 --> 01:51:21.580
[Guest]: constitution because the Indian constitution has simply understood that if you wanted to

01:51:21.580 --> 01:51:28.580
[Guest]: deal with a country of such diversity of language, caste, region, religion, etc., etc., I mean,

01:51:28.580 --> 01:51:32.060
[Guest]: how are you going to accommodate it if you cannot accommodate for various kinds of diversity?

01:51:32.060 --> 01:51:36.740
[Guest]: So as I said, it was never envisaged to be a federal constitution in the technical sense.

01:51:36.740 --> 01:51:41.620
[Guest]: It was a unitary state, but a state which had these various kinds of asymmetric relations

01:51:41.620 --> 01:51:43.700
[Guest]: with various provinces to capture their specific histories.

01:51:43.700 --> 01:51:45.980
[Guest]: Let me just give you one example.

01:51:45.980 --> 01:51:52.100
[Guest]: You know, when the BJP came back to power in 2014, you know, one of the main sort of

01:51:52.100 --> 01:51:56.520
[Guest]: Markway announcements, which was done, was the announcement that we are going to sign

01:51:56.520 --> 01:52:00.220
[Guest]: an agreement with the Nagas, right, which you may recall, the Prime Minister had sort

01:52:00.220 --> 01:52:03.340
[Guest]: of made that announcement as a signing ceremony and so on.

01:52:03.340 --> 01:52:06.860
[Guest]: And as part of that speech, one of the reasons which she explained why we had to sort of

01:52:06.860 --> 01:52:09.240
[Guest]: do this and what the final agreement would look like.

01:52:09.240 --> 01:52:14.700
[Guest]: He said that final agreement will recognize the special history of the Naga people, right?

01:52:14.700 --> 01:52:16.620
[Guest]: Article 370 did exactly that.

01:52:16.620 --> 01:52:18.740
[Guest]: It recognized the special history of this thing.

01:52:18.740 --> 01:52:23.540
[Guest]: The various asymmetric province parts of the constitution recognize the fact, you know,

01:52:23.540 --> 01:52:29.020
[Guest]: because as a historian, what is striking about India is not that, you know, India is an agglomeration

01:52:29.020 --> 01:52:31.680
[Guest]: of various regions, which came together and decided to become a nation.

01:52:31.680 --> 01:52:35.580
[Guest]: It's not like Italy and or like Prussia, which became Germany later.

01:52:35.580 --> 01:52:41.140
[Guest]: The imaginary of the nation and the imaginary of the region in India are both coeval.

01:52:41.140 --> 01:52:43.700
[Guest]: They happen more or less at the same time.

01:52:43.700 --> 01:52:46.500
[Guest]: People feel like I'm part of this region and also part of this nation, right?

01:52:46.500 --> 01:52:51.900
[Guest]: So in a sense, it is that principle which the Indian constitution tried to capture

01:52:51.900 --> 01:52:54.540
[Guest]: by these kinds of various provisions of asymmetry.

01:52:54.540 --> 01:52:59.420
[Guest]: So in a sense, we are going against the grain of our own history and the lay of this land.

01:52:59.420 --> 01:53:02.340
[Guest]: If we are saying that we have to do away with asymmetric provisions, which is why I was

01:53:02.340 --> 01:53:06.660
[Guest]: surprised that, you know, when when the chief minister of Sikkim says that I welcome the

01:53:06.660 --> 01:53:11.140
[Guest]: sort of removal of Article 370, but I'm also assured that my special status or my state

01:53:11.140 --> 01:53:12.140
[Guest]: is going to remain in place.

01:53:12.140 --> 01:53:13.700
[Guest]: I mean, what are the guarantees, right?

01:53:13.700 --> 01:53:17.820
[Guest]: If asymmetry does not apply for one, who can assure it for another in a very different

01:53:17.820 --> 01:53:18.820
[Amit Varma]: context.

01:53:18.820 --> 01:53:23.280
[Amit Varma]: And also, as you pointed out, you know, before we started recording, that there are parties

01:53:23.280 --> 01:53:28.300
[Amit Varma]: like the TDP and the TRS, which would expect them to stand up for federalism and, you know,

01:53:28.300 --> 01:53:32.420
[Amit Varma]: that's practically the raison d'etre, in a sense, and, and yet, they have welcomed this

01:53:32.420 --> 01:53:33.420
[Guest]: move.

01:53:33.420 --> 01:53:37.180
[Guest]: So, so I think, so as far as 370 is concerned, and, you know, I think it raises questions

01:53:37.180 --> 01:53:42.300
[Guest]: about what happens to the future of this kind of asymmetric character of the Indian constitution,

01:53:42.300 --> 01:53:44.140
[Guest]: if it can be eroded in this way.

01:53:44.140 --> 01:53:49.940
[Guest]: The second is about the manner in which the state has been reduced to a union territory,

01:53:49.940 --> 01:53:52.420
[Guest]: you know, bifurcated and reduced to two union territories.

01:53:52.420 --> 01:53:57.420
[Guest]: I think that has very significant consequences and questions it raises about what the nature

01:53:57.420 --> 01:54:01.180
[Guest]: of federalism in this country is going to be going forward, right?

01:54:01.180 --> 01:54:06.100
[Guest]: In the first place, you know, how do you reorganize a province?

01:54:06.100 --> 01:54:08.660
[Guest]: Article three of the Indian constitution lays out what are the things that need to be done.

01:54:08.660 --> 01:54:13.300
[Guest]: And that article three actually had a special requirement for JNK, over and above that of

01:54:13.300 --> 01:54:14.300
[Guest]: every other state.

01:54:14.300 --> 01:54:18.220
[Guest]: For every other state, in order to table a bill for bifurcation of a state, for instance,

01:54:18.220 --> 01:54:22.180
[Guest]: what you needed is a concurrence of the sort of, you know, it had to be tabled before the

01:54:22.180 --> 01:54:23.940
[Guest]: state legislature.

01:54:23.940 --> 01:54:27.860
[Guest]: And then the president could sort of give us approval to be tabled in parliament.

01:54:27.860 --> 01:54:32.540
[Guest]: Whereas with the JNK state, it was specifically laid down under article three, that the concurrence

01:54:32.540 --> 01:54:35.560
[Guest]: of the state legislature had to be gotten before any such thing could be done.

01:54:35.560 --> 01:54:39.660
[Guest]: So it is an additional provision, once again, as part of this extra sort of guarantee of

01:54:39.660 --> 01:54:40.980
[Guest]: autonomy and so on.

01:54:40.980 --> 01:54:42.420
[Guest]: But you've done away with all of that stuff, right?

01:54:42.420 --> 01:54:43.420
[Guest]: Now what have you done?

01:54:43.420 --> 01:54:47.100
[Guest]: You have said basically that we don't even need the concurrence of the state government.

01:54:47.100 --> 01:54:50.840
[Guest]: The president's appointee who is a governor is enough to give concurrence.

01:54:50.840 --> 01:54:51.840
[Guest]: So that is the first thing.

01:54:51.840 --> 01:54:57.580
[Guest]: The second thing is that you have said that, you know, you can carve out a state without

01:54:57.580 --> 01:55:02.060
[Guest]: any reference to the visuals of the legislature of that state, without even reference to them,

01:55:02.060 --> 01:55:05.520
[Guest]: forget asking them for approval, just without any reference, you can do it.

01:55:05.520 --> 01:55:08.740
[Guest]: And again, it tells you what are the kinds of things which can be done to a state like

01:55:08.740 --> 01:55:12.380
[Guest]: JNK and article 370, because you cannot do the same thing with any other state.

01:55:12.380 --> 01:55:16.940
[Amit Varma]: I mean, you did it to a state which had so many protections, and therefore you can basically

01:55:16.940 --> 01:55:18.240
[Amit Varma]: So that's the first thing.

01:55:18.240 --> 01:55:24.820
[Guest]: The second thing is about saying that what does it mean politically for any government

01:55:24.820 --> 01:55:31.940
[Guest]: of India to say that, listen, we can impose president's rule on a state and then say that

01:55:31.940 --> 01:55:35.860
[Guest]: the governor's concurrence is sufficient to not just carve out that state, but to reduce

01:55:35.860 --> 01:55:40.880
[Guest]: various parts of the state from statehood to union territory status.

01:55:40.880 --> 01:55:45.060
[Guest]: So tomorrow, you know, hypothetically, we can think about some other ruling party, which

01:55:45.060 --> 01:55:50.420
[Guest]: might be in power, which may decide that in order to take political control of a state,

01:55:50.420 --> 01:55:55.420
[Guest]: which we cannot win elections in, we are just going to wait it out, impose president's rule,

01:55:55.420 --> 01:55:58.860
[Guest]: bring in a bill, carving out that state into a series of union territories, emasculating

01:55:58.860 --> 01:56:00.320
[Guest]: it politically.

01:56:00.320 --> 01:56:01.860
[Guest]: And we are done with the thing.

01:56:01.860 --> 01:56:05.660
[Guest]: I mean, what a change that would mean for Indian democracy and federalism, you can imagine.

01:56:05.660 --> 01:56:09.860
[Guest]: Now, I'm not suggesting that this is going to be replicated, but everything creates some

01:56:09.860 --> 01:56:10.860
[Guest]: precedent.

01:56:10.860 --> 01:56:11.860
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:56:11.860 --> 01:56:15.540
[Guest]: So we have to think about what kinds of precedents we are setting for ourselves as a country.

01:56:15.540 --> 01:56:21.300
[Guest]: If we are going to accept that these are sort of legitimate means of doing democratic business.

01:56:21.300 --> 01:56:24.380
[Amit Varma]: And just thinking aloud, I think once you change the rules of the game, you change the

01:56:24.380 --> 01:56:25.380
[Amit Varma]: game.

01:56:25.380 --> 01:56:28.380
[Amit Varma]: Even if you don't apply those rules necessarily, everybody's incentives change.

01:56:28.380 --> 01:56:29.380
[Amit Varma]: Precisely.

01:56:29.380 --> 01:56:36.140
[Amit Varma]: So I have sort of three broader questions, which are all things about which I'm genuinely

01:56:36.140 --> 01:56:37.140
[Amit Varma]: puzzled.

01:56:37.140 --> 01:56:44.620
[Amit Varma]: One, in one case, it is evident that 370 was sort of a compact between the Union of India

01:56:44.620 --> 01:56:46.580
[Amit Varma]: and Jammu and Kashmir.

01:56:46.580 --> 01:56:51.260
[Amit Varma]: And that we have broken this compact by doing what we have done.

01:56:51.260 --> 01:56:55.260
[Amit Varma]: And you could argue that, you know, Nehru himself broke the contact repeatedly.

01:56:55.260 --> 01:56:58.700
[Amit Varma]: And what has happened now is just a formalizing of that.

01:56:58.700 --> 01:57:02.380
[Amit Varma]: But the larger question here is broken the compact with who?

01:57:02.380 --> 01:57:07.420
[Amit Varma]: Because even the original compact wasn't with an elected leaders who represented the will

01:57:07.420 --> 01:57:08.420
[Amit Varma]: of the people.

01:57:08.420 --> 01:57:09.900
[Amit Varma]: We never knew the will of the people.

01:57:09.900 --> 01:57:12.500
[Amit Varma]: I would say we still don't know the will of the people.

01:57:12.500 --> 01:57:15.060
[Amit Varma]: And also the will of the people is not a monolithic thing.

01:57:15.060 --> 01:57:19.340
[Amit Varma]: Not only are there many different kinds of people with different wills, but also over

01:57:19.340 --> 01:57:25.060
[Amit Varma]: a period of time, what the Kashmiri people might want has also changed rapidly, whether

01:57:25.060 --> 01:57:30.780
[Amit Varma]: you're talking about 1955, or you're talking about 75, or you're talking about 1990, after

01:57:30.780 --> 01:57:35.700
[Amit Varma]: everything kind of blows up, or you're talking about 2007, when things were better, and you're

01:57:35.700 --> 01:57:39.500
[Amit Varma]: talking about now when things are really pretty bad.

01:57:39.500 --> 01:57:44.660
[Amit Varma]: So the issue is, you know, some people would raise the point, which I have a fair amount

01:57:44.660 --> 01:57:51.900
[Amit Varma]: of sympathy for that the current beleaguered young Kashmiri, who views the Indian government

01:57:51.900 --> 01:57:57.500
[Amit Varma]: as an oppressive foreign power, if he wants to fight for freedom today, he is basically

01:57:57.500 --> 01:58:03.660
[Amit Varma]: not on a lower moral plane than say, a Bhagat Singh or a Chandrashekhar Azad or any of the

01:58:03.660 --> 01:58:10.460
[Amit Varma]: Indian freedom fighters were, you see yourself as a local people fighting this colonial force.

01:58:10.460 --> 01:58:13.780
[Amit Varma]: And the fact is that they have been promised self determination for so many years.

01:58:13.780 --> 01:58:17.540
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, and of course, the meaning of that term has changed for them what self

01:58:17.540 --> 01:58:19.700
[Amit Varma]: determination really means.

01:58:19.700 --> 01:58:24.860
[Amit Varma]: How do we reconcile that question, like so far, we've discussed Kashmir as a geopolitical

01:58:24.860 --> 01:58:29.900
[Amit Varma]: issue between India and Pakistan, and, you know, as a political issue within India, where

01:58:29.900 --> 01:58:32.340
[Amit Varma]: all this other politics is playing out?

01:58:32.340 --> 01:58:37.420
[Amit Varma]: What about the moral question that the people sort of also have a right to decide their

01:58:37.420 --> 01:58:38.420
[Amit Varma]: own destiny?

01:58:38.420 --> 01:58:42.980
[Guest]: Well, I think, at some level, you know, that is the fundamental question, right?

01:58:42.980 --> 01:58:49.300
[Guest]: Which is to say that, is it really possible for any government in any part of the world

01:58:49.300 --> 01:58:54.940
[Guest]: to be able to impose its will on ordinary people over very long periods of time?

01:58:54.940 --> 01:59:00.380
[Guest]: And I think much of modern history suggests that that is unlikely to work in a long term

01:59:00.380 --> 01:59:01.380
[Guest]: context, right?

01:59:01.380 --> 01:59:03.540
[Guest]: You can do it for some lengths of period, you can maybe do it for very long periods

01:59:03.540 --> 01:59:06.300
[Guest]: of time, but unlikely that it's going to continue forever, right?

01:59:06.300 --> 01:59:11.060
[Guest]: I mean, in that sense, there is no permanence to that kind of dominance, and so on.

01:59:11.060 --> 01:59:15.980
[Guest]: Now, as far as Kashmir itself is concerned, see, we have gone through so many sort of

01:59:15.980 --> 01:59:21.860
[Guest]: stages of thinking about how do we refer to the will of the people, almost from the moment

01:59:21.860 --> 01:59:25.940
[Guest]: when this pledge was made that in Junagadh, Hyderabad, Kashmir, we are going to refer

01:59:25.940 --> 01:59:28.740
[Guest]: to the will of the people, you wanted to know what that would be.

01:59:28.740 --> 01:59:30.180
[Guest]: Should it be a referendum?

01:59:30.180 --> 01:59:31.180
[Guest]: Should it be a plebiscite?

01:59:31.180 --> 01:59:33.620
[Guest]: Those are technically somewhat different things.

01:59:33.620 --> 01:59:38.300
[Guest]: Should it be a Indian referendum or an Indian plebiscite or should it be internationally

01:59:38.300 --> 01:59:39.300
[Guest]: supervised?

01:59:39.300 --> 01:59:40.300
[Guest]: Right?

01:59:40.300 --> 01:59:41.300
[Guest]: There was that question.

01:59:41.300 --> 01:59:45.940
[Guest]: Later on, there was this question of saying that is the Constituent Assembly of JNK, which

01:59:45.940 --> 01:59:50.300
[Guest]: we have assured under our constitution, and that constitution is that a form of self-determination?

01:59:50.300 --> 01:59:54.380
[Guest]: Now, you said earlier that, you know, the Kashmiri people themselves were never asked.

01:59:54.380 --> 01:59:57.620
[Guest]: But in a sense, that is broadly true of the Indian constitution also.

01:59:57.620 --> 02:00:01.860
[Guest]: It was elected on a limited franchise, the Constituent Assembly, and the constitution

02:00:01.860 --> 02:00:05.100
[Guest]: was never ratified by the people, though you could think of the first general election

02:00:05.100 --> 02:00:10.700
[Guest]: in 1951 as broadly a ratification of the constitution, but it was not technically not a ratification.

02:00:10.700 --> 02:00:15.580
[Guest]: So my only point is to say that just because that was not done, it does not mean that,

02:00:15.580 --> 02:00:19.020
[Guest]: you know, everything had to be only solved by means of plebiscites and referenda.

02:00:19.020 --> 02:00:20.020
[Guest]: Right?

02:00:20.020 --> 02:00:23.060
[Guest]: I mean, there could have been other ways of sort of doing those things.

02:00:23.060 --> 02:00:28.340
[Guest]: Then we had a constitution coming in, but that constitution has been under article 370

02:00:28.340 --> 02:00:29.340
[Guest]: eroded.

02:00:29.340 --> 02:00:33.260
[Guest]: And, you know, Indian leaders starting with Jawaharlal Nehru have somewhat openly accepted

02:00:33.260 --> 02:00:34.260
[Guest]: that they were doing it.

02:00:34.260 --> 02:00:35.260
[Guest]: Right?

02:00:35.260 --> 02:00:37.220
[Guest]: When Gulzarilal Nanda says you've driven a tunnel through this stuff.

02:00:37.220 --> 02:00:38.220
[Guest]: Very good.

02:00:38.220 --> 02:00:39.220
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:00:39.220 --> 02:00:40.740
[Guest]: And we are proudly announcing that we are doing it.

02:00:40.740 --> 02:00:43.580
[Guest]: It's not something that we are trying to hide as a fact.

02:00:43.580 --> 02:00:48.260
[Guest]: Subsequently, in 1965, when Prime Minister Lal Bahadur Shastri was the thing, something

02:00:48.260 --> 02:00:49.740
[Guest]: even worse was done.

02:00:49.740 --> 02:00:54.860
[Guest]: The state JNK state government effectively was converted from a national conference government

02:00:54.860 --> 02:00:57.260
[Guest]: to a Congress Party government.

02:00:57.260 --> 02:01:01.740
[Guest]: And they amended the Kashmir constitution using their provisions of constitution amendment

02:01:01.740 --> 02:01:07.540
[Guest]: to make the elected Sadre Riyasat into a governor appointed by the center and also imported

02:01:07.540 --> 02:01:10.820
[Guest]: provisions under article 370 for imposition of president's rule.

02:01:10.820 --> 02:01:15.340
[Guest]: Just imagine a total fundamental change in the way that that thing happened.

02:01:15.340 --> 02:01:19.620
[Guest]: The agreement between Indira Gandhi and Sheikh Abdullah, which led to Sheikh Abdullah's return

02:01:19.620 --> 02:01:26.220
[Guest]: to power in 1975, again was on the premise that a number of powers which were vested

02:01:26.220 --> 02:01:27.900
[Guest]: in the JNK constitution would be the same.

02:01:27.900 --> 02:01:32.820
[Guest]: For instance, one of the key clauses of that Sheikh Abdullah-Indira Gandhi agreement was

02:01:32.820 --> 02:01:37.940
[Guest]: that the JNK constitution could not in any way legislate on the powers of the governor

02:01:37.940 --> 02:01:38.940
[Guest]: of the state.

02:01:38.940 --> 02:01:43.140
[Guest]: So effectively, you first made the governor an instrument of the center.

02:01:43.140 --> 02:01:46.060
[Guest]: You said through the instrument of the center, president's rule can be imposed.

02:01:46.060 --> 02:01:48.700
[Guest]: Then you say that the state's constitution cannot touch the governor at all.

02:01:48.700 --> 02:01:53.300
[Guest]: So effectively, you have sort of eroded the autonomy of the state in every conceivable

02:01:53.300 --> 02:01:54.300
[Guest]: way.

02:01:54.300 --> 02:01:59.420
[Guest]: In 1986, when the state was under governor's rule, Mr. Jagmohan was the governor at that

02:01:59.420 --> 02:02:03.420
[Guest]: point of time and Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi was there, they extended further provisions

02:02:03.420 --> 02:02:07.020
[Guest]: of the Indian constitution without any reference to anyone saying the governor is there to

02:02:07.020 --> 02:02:08.020
[Guest]: give concurrence.

02:02:08.020 --> 02:02:13.380
[Guest]: We know from historical records that even the law secretary of India had raised a sort

02:02:13.380 --> 02:02:17.740
[Guest]: of red flag saying that this is a dubious sort of move because the governor cannot stand

02:02:17.740 --> 02:02:18.740
[Guest]: it.

02:02:18.740 --> 02:02:19.740
[Guest]: But we said we will do it.

02:02:19.740 --> 02:02:25.100
[Guest]: So at every point of time, therefore, as you are saying, we have promised different kinds

02:02:25.100 --> 02:02:28.580
[Guest]: of self-determination or given them a different opportunity to say that, listen, we will allow

02:02:28.580 --> 02:02:29.580
[Guest]: you to have elections.

02:02:29.580 --> 02:02:32.300
[Guest]: Then in 1987, elections are rigged, right?

02:02:32.300 --> 02:02:37.420
[Guest]: So it is in that context that I think we have to understand the despair of the Kashmiris,

02:02:37.420 --> 02:02:43.140
[Guest]: which is to say that, you know, what is it that India says that we can take at face value

02:02:43.140 --> 02:02:46.580
[Guest]: or we can believe that India will stand by it because they are the stronger power.

02:02:46.580 --> 02:02:50.220
[Guest]: You know, there was a very nice article in the Hindu by Suhasini Haider, you know, she

02:02:50.220 --> 02:02:55.020
[Guest]: quoted to Thukdi D's as saying that the strong can do what they can and the weak must endure

02:02:55.020 --> 02:02:56.940
[Guest]: what they must, right?

02:02:56.940 --> 02:02:58.660
[Guest]: From the Malian dialogue.

02:02:58.660 --> 02:03:03.460
[Guest]: Now, if that is the position of the Kashmiris, then their despair is understandable because

02:03:03.460 --> 02:03:06.420
[Guest]: we have promised them many, many things in different ways.

02:03:06.420 --> 02:03:11.880
[Guest]: And what has now been done in a sense, not just is injurious to their thing, it adds

02:03:11.880 --> 02:03:17.660
[Guest]: insult to injury because now you're told that you don't even have the status of a state.

02:03:17.660 --> 02:03:24.220
[Guest]: One of the largest princely states of India has not only been absorbed into the Indian

02:03:24.220 --> 02:03:28.660
[Guest]: Union, you know, whatever, even if you think abolishing Article 370 means any greater integration,

02:03:28.660 --> 02:03:31.460
[Guest]: I don't believe there was any such further thing happening.

02:03:31.460 --> 02:03:35.780
[Guest]: But you reduced it to the state of Union Territory, and you held out a hope to them that they

02:03:35.780 --> 02:03:41.380
[Guest]: can rise up to the state level, if in the future, they sort of behave appropriately.

02:03:41.380 --> 02:03:47.700
[Guest]: Now, I think, you know, that is going to be a matter of deep resentment in Kashmir.

02:03:47.700 --> 02:03:51.020
[Guest]: We will have to see how future politics plays out.

02:03:51.020 --> 02:03:52.020
[Guest]: Nobody knows.

02:03:52.020 --> 02:03:58.180
[Amit Varma]: So I'll come to my second of three questions, sort of by also addressing what people might

02:03:58.180 --> 02:04:02.460
[Amit Varma]: say about self-determination being a slippery slope, for example, somebody might ask, what

02:04:02.460 --> 02:04:06.260
[Amit Varma]: if the people of Andheri want to be independent, where do you stop?

02:04:06.260 --> 02:04:10.860
[Amit Varma]: And what if the people of Warsaw then want to be independent from Andheri, which they

02:04:10.860 --> 02:04:11.860
[Amit Varma]: should?

02:04:11.860 --> 02:04:19.580
[Amit Varma]: And my response to that would by and large be that, I think, even as far as disaffection

02:04:19.580 --> 02:04:24.700
[Amit Varma]: of the Kashmiri people is concerned, they've been based on shifting sands, they have not

02:04:24.700 --> 02:04:27.060
[Amit Varma]: always been pissed off at the Union.

02:04:27.060 --> 02:04:31.740
[Amit Varma]: And in the rest of the country, what we have done is there is some semblance of good governance

02:04:31.740 --> 02:04:35.180
[Amit Varma]: and the rule of law and so on and so forth.

02:04:35.180 --> 02:04:39.060
[Amit Varma]: And the people can actually feel that okay, we are in a democracy, we have some chance,

02:04:39.060 --> 02:04:44.420
[Amit Varma]: we are not unequal compared to the other citizens of this great democracy.

02:04:44.420 --> 02:04:50.340
[Amit Varma]: But what has happened in Kashmir is that the way the state has behaved is with the people

02:04:50.340 --> 02:04:53.740
[Amit Varma]: is very different from say, Warsaw or Andheri.

02:04:53.740 --> 02:04:58.340
[Amit Varma]: I wrote an essay a while back, which I'll also link from the show notes, which sort

02:04:58.340 --> 02:05:03.140
[Amit Varma]: of took off on a lot of counterinsurgency literature I was reading and also David Devadas's

02:05:03.140 --> 02:05:06.900
[Amit Varma]: book, The Generation of Rage in Kashmir, which I'll also link from the show notes where

02:05:06.900 --> 02:05:11.820
[Amit Varma]: Devadas's point was that by 2007, basically a new generation had come up in Kashmir and

02:05:11.820 --> 02:05:17.340
[Amit Varma]: it was much more hopeful and aspirational, and so on and wanting to integrate with India.

02:05:17.340 --> 02:05:22.300
[Amit Varma]: But then the continued brutality by the state sort of, you know, caused them to rise up

02:05:22.300 --> 02:05:24.960
[Amit Varma]: against the state and just made things much worse.

02:05:24.960 --> 02:05:30.960
[Amit Varma]: Not the fault of this government alone, starting from the UPA government 2007-2008 onwards,

02:05:30.960 --> 02:05:31.960
[Amit Varma]: it got much worse.

02:05:31.960 --> 02:05:36.420
[Amit Varma]: And that brings me to a question of strategy on which again, you are an expert is that

02:05:36.420 --> 02:05:42.820
[Amit Varma]: what we have sort of learned from counterinsurgency literature, you know, right from Mao and T.E.

02:05:42.820 --> 02:05:47.020
[Amit Varma]: Lawrence's Seven Pillars of Wisdom and David Galula's books, is that if you are going to

02:05:47.020 --> 02:05:53.100
[Amit Varma]: tackle an insurgency, you don't do it with brute force, you do it with, you know, an

02:05:53.100 --> 02:05:57.980
[Amit Varma]: equation someone once came up with, which is 20% military, 80% political.

02:05:57.980 --> 02:06:02.100
[Amit Varma]: And the key there is that you have to have the local people on your side, so that the

02:06:02.100 --> 02:06:04.980
[Amit Varma]: insurgency doesn't have a place to hide.

02:06:04.980 --> 02:06:09.500
[Amit Varma]: And what instead we have done in Kashmir is instead of providing good governance and getting

02:06:09.500 --> 02:06:15.100
[Amit Varma]: the local people on your side, we have instead alienated the common man far more, made the

02:06:15.100 --> 02:06:20.380
[Amit Varma]: common person sympathetic to freedom fighters and terrorists, whatever one chooses to call

02:06:20.380 --> 02:06:21.380
[Amit Varma]: them.

02:06:21.380 --> 02:06:25.100
[Amit Varma]: And therefore made sure that even if we have Kashmir with us, we don't have the Kashmiri

02:06:25.100 --> 02:06:26.340
[Amit Varma]: with us.

02:06:26.340 --> 02:06:27.340
[Guest]: What are your thoughts on this?

02:06:27.340 --> 02:06:30.700
[Guest]: Well, I think that has been a challenge even before the insurgency began.

02:06:30.700 --> 02:06:36.060
[Guest]: And I think in some ways, the insurgency began as a response to this feeling that normal

02:06:36.060 --> 02:06:40.980
[Guest]: ways of, you know, dealing with India in normal politics, elections, negotiations are not

02:06:40.980 --> 02:06:41.980
[Guest]: going to do.

02:06:41.980 --> 02:06:45.100
[Guest]: So that's how an insurgent sort of group began.

02:06:45.100 --> 02:06:49.520
[Guest]: And as you're saying, you know, the fact that the Indian government also sort of responded

02:06:49.520 --> 02:06:54.020
[Guest]: with an iron fist meant that, you know, the local population then continued to support

02:06:54.020 --> 02:06:57.020
[Guest]: the insurgency to varying degrees over periods of time.

02:06:57.020 --> 02:06:59.980
[Guest]: As you're rightly saying, there have been periods when Kashmiris have been more or less

02:06:59.980 --> 02:07:00.980
[Guest]: hopeful.

02:07:00.980 --> 02:07:04.660
[Guest]: You know, I'm not in a position to say whether in 2007, there was a new generation of Kashmiris

02:07:04.660 --> 02:07:06.940
[Amit Varma]: who are more hopeful or not.

02:07:06.940 --> 02:07:07.940
[Amit Varma]: That is Devadas's claim.

02:07:07.940 --> 02:07:08.940
[Guest]: And it's very interesting.

02:07:08.940 --> 02:07:10.100
[Guest]: Yeah, it's an interesting claim.

02:07:10.100 --> 02:07:14.220
[Guest]: But I think what is empirically true on in a sense, superficially, you know, you can

02:07:14.220 --> 02:07:19.220
[Guest]: sort of immediately sort of take it as granted that there is a generation of Kashmiris, which

02:07:19.220 --> 02:07:24.660
[Guest]: came of age by the late 2000s, who had practically grown up in the shadow of the insurgency.

02:07:24.660 --> 02:07:28.660
[Guest]: At least, you know, the generations which preceded them knew something of what life

02:07:28.660 --> 02:07:30.820
[Guest]: was before the insurgency began.

02:07:30.820 --> 02:07:35.100
[Guest]: And this, you know, very strong degree of sort of security response, which, you know,

02:07:35.100 --> 02:07:36.460
[Guest]: is a consequence of the insurgency.

02:07:36.460 --> 02:07:40.780
[Guest]: And again, I wouldn't want to sort of carry a brief for the insurgency in Kashmir, because,

02:07:40.780 --> 02:07:44.860
[Guest]: you know, the fact is that the Indian Army's presence was not as overweening in Kashmir

02:07:44.860 --> 02:07:46.220
[Guest]: before the insurgency began.

02:07:46.220 --> 02:07:48.460
[Guest]: It is a response to what the insurgency is.

02:07:48.460 --> 02:07:51.240
[Guest]: And the insurgency has also brutalized the people of Kashmir.

02:07:51.240 --> 02:07:54.560
[Guest]: It is not a unilateral sort of brutalization, which has been done by the Indian Army.

02:07:54.560 --> 02:07:59.500
[Amit Varma]: There are many unpalatable elements of the insurgency, such as recent Islamism, the jihadism

02:07:59.500 --> 02:08:00.500
[Amit Varma]: that has come in.

02:08:00.500 --> 02:08:05.380
[Amit Varma]: So I'm not trying to pass a judgment in as an army good insurgency bad, or the other

02:08:05.380 --> 02:08:06.380
[Guest]: way around.

02:08:06.380 --> 02:08:07.380
[Guest]: Absolutely.

02:08:07.380 --> 02:08:08.380
[Guest]: No, I fully agree.

02:08:08.380 --> 02:08:11.860
[Guest]: But all I'm trying to say is that for the ordinary Kashmiri, they have had to deal with

02:08:11.860 --> 02:08:16.100
[Guest]: the consequences of living in an environment which was dominated by an insurgency counter

02:08:16.100 --> 02:08:17.100
[Guest]: insurgency dynamic.

02:08:17.100 --> 02:08:18.100
[Guest]: Right?

02:08:18.100 --> 02:08:23.900
[Guest]: It is not a straightforward question of saying that this is just a pure sort of Israeli occupation

02:08:23.900 --> 02:08:24.900
[Guest]: of the West Bank.

02:08:24.900 --> 02:08:26.380
[Guest]: There is no insurgency happening in the West Bank.

02:08:26.380 --> 02:08:27.380
[Guest]: Right?

02:08:27.380 --> 02:08:30.020
[Guest]: I mean, there is a very different situation out here, which in some ways much worse possibly.

02:08:30.020 --> 02:08:34.700
[Guest]: Which is why I'm saying that for a generation of Kashmiris, what they have grown up is under

02:08:34.700 --> 02:08:40.140
[Guest]: the shadow of the gun, whether it is wielded by the insurgents or by the security forces.

02:08:40.140 --> 02:08:44.080
[Guest]: And that obviously has huge psychological implications for the way that they think about

02:08:44.080 --> 02:08:47.660
[Guest]: their future, about what they want, what they are willing to risk.

02:08:47.660 --> 02:08:50.940
[Guest]: You know, in the last couple of years, we have seen newspaper reporting.

02:08:50.940 --> 02:08:55.860
[Guest]: I have not been to Kashmir, but I've been reading newspaper reports, suggesting that

02:08:55.860 --> 02:09:00.540
[Guest]: people are actually preventing the security forces from carrying out operations by forming

02:09:00.540 --> 02:09:01.540
[Guest]: human shields.

02:09:01.540 --> 02:09:05.380
[Guest]: And, you know, actually sort of risking death effectively, because they can get, you know,

02:09:05.380 --> 02:09:08.460
[Guest]: they may be collateral damage in an operation, ongoing operation, if you come in between

02:09:08.460 --> 02:09:09.460
[Guest]: and so on.

02:09:09.460 --> 02:09:13.100
[Guest]: Now, all of that suggests a degree of despair, which is very high.

02:09:13.100 --> 02:09:17.620
[Guest]: And I think the challenge for us is now to say that, listen, how are we going to deal

02:09:17.620 --> 02:09:18.620
[Guest]: with that?

02:09:18.620 --> 02:09:20.940
[Guest]: That is the human element, and that is also the moral element.

02:09:20.940 --> 02:09:25.020
[Guest]: Because at the end of the day, you know, there is this famous line from the Vietnam War,

02:09:25.020 --> 02:09:26.020
[Guest]: right?

02:09:26.020 --> 02:09:31.300
[Guest]: I mean, it may be an apocryphal story where an American sort of Marines captain, you know,

02:09:31.300 --> 02:09:35.540
[Guest]: is interviewed by some news agencies immediately after the taking over of some village which

02:09:35.540 --> 02:09:40.580
[Guest]: has been strafed and bombed and they've captured it and says, you know, what, why did you have

02:09:40.580 --> 02:09:42.620
[Guest]: to do sort of, you know, use so much force?

02:09:42.620 --> 02:09:45.860
[Guest]: He says, we had to destroy the village in order to save it.

02:09:45.860 --> 02:09:47.220
[Guest]: That is a question we have to ask ourselves.

02:09:47.220 --> 02:09:51.020
[Guest]: Are we going to destroy people in order to save them?

02:09:51.020 --> 02:09:53.660
[Guest]: It's a mistake that we made in so many other guises in the past, right?

02:09:53.660 --> 02:09:59.500
[Guest]: We believe that in order to affirm our secular value, we have to keep somebody else in subjection.

02:09:59.500 --> 02:10:02.520
[Guest]: Then how does it mean an affirmation of any democratic values?

02:10:02.520 --> 02:10:06.220
[Guest]: So I think the question of means and ends, which is rightly posed, is today, I think,

02:10:06.220 --> 02:10:11.580
[Guest]: an even more urgent one, because the insurgency, at least in the short term, is likely to get

02:10:11.580 --> 02:10:17.620
[Guest]: some kind of a flip, because, you know, Pakistan will feel emboldened to sort of fish in troubled

02:10:17.620 --> 02:10:21.420
[Guest]: waters, you know, there may be more disaffected youth within Kashmir who may be willing to

02:10:21.420 --> 02:10:26.460
[Guest]: take up the gun, or they may not be, but let's assume that the insurgency and counter insurgency

02:10:26.460 --> 02:10:29.820
[Guest]: dynamic is not going away anytime soon, just because you abolished Article 370, that's

02:10:29.820 --> 02:10:30.820
[Amit Varma]: not going away.

02:10:30.820 --> 02:10:33.620
[Amit Varma]: No, and the point of my question was also to say, like you used to phrase the shadow

02:10:33.620 --> 02:10:34.620
[Amit Varma]: of the gun.

02:10:34.620 --> 02:10:38.380
[Amit Varma]: And the thing is, the fact that there are so many young people living under the shadow

02:10:38.380 --> 02:10:43.900
[Amit Varma]: of the gun, who have seen their 12 year old brothers taken from home and shot in front

02:10:43.900 --> 02:10:47.620
[Amit Varma]: of a wall, and so on and so forth, that they've seen all this brutality unfold on their friends

02:10:47.620 --> 02:10:52.460
[Amit Varma]: and family, and others, and the point is, the shadow of the gun is actually the worst

02:10:52.460 --> 02:10:57.900
[Amit Varma]: way to fight the insurgency, you know, which is a lesson that we've learned over the decades.

02:10:57.900 --> 02:11:02.460
[Amit Varma]: And that if the Modi government wanted, it could just fight the insurgency in a very

02:11:02.460 --> 02:11:06.500
[Amit Varma]: different way by providing good governance, trying to win the people over.

02:11:06.500 --> 02:11:11.180
[Amit Varma]: And that would be far more successful in integrating Kashmir into India in the long run, if they

02:11:11.180 --> 02:11:12.180
[Amit Varma]: want to.

02:11:12.180 --> 02:11:15.380
[Amit Varma]: Is that kind of understanding not there within the

02:11:15.380 --> 02:11:20.580
[Guest]: You know, Amit, let me try and explain what I think they are thinking, right, beyond this

02:11:20.580 --> 02:11:21.580
[Guest]: Article 370.

02:11:21.580 --> 02:11:25.500
[Guest]: Because there are important sort of glimpses we got of their reasoning behind this move

02:11:25.500 --> 02:11:28.500
[Guest]: from the Prime Minister's speeches, from the Home Minister's speeches, which I think,

02:11:28.500 --> 02:11:31.740
[Guest]: as analysts and observers, we should take seriously, right.

02:11:31.740 --> 02:11:35.840
[Guest]: In fact, I think in some ways, the Prime Minister concurs with what you said, which is that governance

02:11:35.840 --> 02:11:37.220
[Guest]: has not been good in Kashmir.

02:11:37.220 --> 02:11:41.100
[Guest]: In fact, he said in his speech, that ever since the imposition of governor's rule, we

02:11:41.100 --> 02:11:43.220
[Guest]: have managed to do many more schemes, etc, etc.

02:11:43.220 --> 02:11:46.860
[Guest]: Now, whether that's an empirically true fact or not, and to what extent all of that is

02:11:46.860 --> 02:11:48.300
[Guest]: done is a different question.

02:11:48.300 --> 02:11:54.300
[Guest]: But he shares this assumption that the existing status quo has not delivered any governance.

02:11:54.300 --> 02:11:56.500
[Amit Varma]: But things have actually become worse in the last five years.

02:11:56.500 --> 02:11:57.500
[Guest]: Maybe.

02:11:57.500 --> 02:12:00.060
[Guest]: As I said, I mean, you know, let's say, but all I'm trying to say is that they will share

02:12:00.060 --> 02:12:04.080
[Guest]: the diagnosis in some way, right, and they just have a different solution to the problem.

02:12:04.080 --> 02:12:08.660
[Guest]: And as I sort of read their sort of speeches and explanations, I think the way that they

02:12:08.660 --> 02:12:13.060
[Guest]: are thinking about it is to say that what Kashmir needs is actually a new kind of a

02:12:13.060 --> 02:12:16.700
[Guest]: political dispensation altogether, that, you know, and the Prime Minister has spoken many

02:12:16.700 --> 02:12:19.940
[Guest]: times about the three families which have looted Kashmir and so on, right, I mean, you

02:12:19.940 --> 02:12:21.340
[Guest]: would have recalled from his speech.

02:12:21.340 --> 02:12:25.700
[Guest]: So I think they now have come to a conclusion that we need a new generation of leaders in

02:12:25.700 --> 02:12:30.860
[Guest]: Kashmir, who will be willing to work with India, and can be sort of, you know, can sort

02:12:30.860 --> 02:12:34.700
[Guest]: of pursue an agenda in tandem with New Delhi, which would be very different from that in

02:12:34.700 --> 02:12:35.700
[Guest]: the past.

02:12:35.700 --> 02:12:36.700
[Guest]: Right.

02:12:36.700 --> 02:12:39.340
[Guest]: And in order to do that, we have to create a totally new political context.

02:12:39.340 --> 02:12:43.100
[Guest]: And which is why we started the level of panchayats, because we are hoping that a bottoms up sort

02:12:43.100 --> 02:12:47.720
[Guest]: of process of elections, etc, will force up new leaders to come.

02:12:47.720 --> 02:12:50.020
[Guest]: And those leaders will have to operate under a very different context.

02:12:50.020 --> 02:12:53.540
[Guest]: Because now, the main challenge for Kashmir is to get back statehood, which has been promised

02:12:53.540 --> 02:12:57.420
[Guest]: to them, at least implicitly, from Union Territory status.

02:12:57.420 --> 02:13:03.480
[Guest]: And now the political lines of Jammu Kashmir, the new Union Territory, are going to be drawn

02:13:03.480 --> 02:13:04.540
[Guest]: in different ways.

02:13:04.540 --> 02:13:08.820
[Guest]: And it's not very clear that the Kashmiris will have the kind of political dominance

02:13:08.820 --> 02:13:11.140
[Guest]: that they had in the previous dispensation, right.

02:13:11.140 --> 02:13:16.260
[Guest]: So a new politics is being created, which I think is one of their stated intentions.

02:13:16.260 --> 02:13:21.900
[Guest]: And the claim is that that politics will lead to newer forms of dealing with this problem,

02:13:21.900 --> 02:13:24.340
[Guest]: which will be much better than what we have tried in the past.

02:13:24.340 --> 02:13:27.940
[Guest]: Now I think to be fair, we should grant them that this is the reconstruction.

02:13:27.940 --> 02:13:32.260
[Guest]: Now whether this works or not, I myself feel a little skeptical, because, you know, as

02:13:32.260 --> 02:13:35.140
[Guest]: a historian, unfortunately, I am stuck in the past, right, people like me are told you're

02:13:35.140 --> 02:13:36.140
[Guest]: stuck in the past.

02:13:36.140 --> 02:13:37.140
[Guest]: Yes, I am stuck in the past.

02:13:37.140 --> 02:13:39.280
[Guest]: Because that's I studied the past for this thing.

02:13:39.280 --> 02:13:43.540
[Guest]: But when I look at leaders as stalwart as Sheikh Abdullah, you know, who, whether in

02:13:43.540 --> 02:13:49.020
[Guest]: 1952, after the Delhi Agreement, or in 1975, after his agreement with Indira Gandhi, felt

02:13:49.020 --> 02:13:53.780
[Guest]: that he could not really sort of sell the same agreement to his people.

02:13:53.780 --> 02:13:59.140
[Guest]: If stalwart leaders like that felt about agreements of autonomy, is it realistic to assume that

02:13:59.140 --> 02:14:03.100
[Guest]: there will be new leaders who will come out of the situation in Kashmir, who will say

02:14:03.100 --> 02:14:06.740
[Guest]: that no, actually, statehood, you know, is the main sort of objective for us, we should

02:14:06.740 --> 02:14:08.940
[Guest]: be happy with what is there.

02:14:08.940 --> 02:14:09.940
[Guest]: Maybe they will.

02:14:09.940 --> 02:14:11.640
[Guest]: I'm not saying that it is impossible.

02:14:11.640 --> 02:14:16.060
[Guest]: But as a student of history, it seems to me that there are limits to the plasticity of

02:14:16.060 --> 02:14:17.500
[Guest]: politics in Kashmir.

02:14:17.500 --> 02:14:19.380
[Guest]: It is not infinitely malleable.

02:14:19.380 --> 02:14:23.180
[Guest]: There are certain things and that is the nature of every democratic process.

02:14:23.180 --> 02:14:27.220
[Guest]: And it is not just India, but any country which has dealt, you know, you look at Americans,

02:14:27.220 --> 02:14:30.740
[Guest]: you know, they wanted someone like Hamid Karzai to be in Afghanistan.

02:14:30.740 --> 02:14:34.900
[Guest]: But Hamid Karzai then turns out to be a very difficult actor for you to deal with because

02:14:34.900 --> 02:14:38.740
[Guest]: his incentives are not to toe your line all the time, or to do exactly what you want.

02:14:38.740 --> 02:14:43.040
[Guest]: You may both want the same thing, which is overall development, etc.

02:14:43.040 --> 02:14:46.900
[Guest]: But his idea of how that has to be accomplished, cuts across with yours.

02:14:46.900 --> 02:14:50.380
[Guest]: Same thing happened with Ingo Dindium in South Vietnam back in the day, right?

02:14:50.380 --> 02:14:55.580
[Guest]: So I don't see, therefore, that democratic politics is as capable of being shaped by

02:14:55.580 --> 02:14:58.540
[Guest]: grand designs, as we seem to assume.

02:14:58.540 --> 02:15:03.700
[Guest]: But we have made a start, it's a, it's a start, which has torn up the past, broken away from

02:15:03.700 --> 02:15:05.620
[Guest]: it in a very dramatic way.

02:15:05.620 --> 02:15:08.820
[Guest]: Even if it has used the same means that were used in the past, but I think still this is

02:15:08.820 --> 02:15:12.700
[Guest]: a step, an order of magnitude, different kind of decision which has been taken, we'll have

02:15:12.700 --> 02:15:13.700
[Amit Varma]: to see how it plays out.

02:15:13.700 --> 02:15:16.380
[Amit Varma]: I mean, the future is all unknown unknowns.

02:15:16.380 --> 02:15:20.620
[Amit Varma]: And for my last question, I want to shift the context a little bit, where I am going

02:15:20.620 --> 02:15:26.420
[Amit Varma]: to say, let's not talk about how constitution or non constitutional 370 is.

02:15:26.420 --> 02:15:31.860
[Amit Varma]: Let's not even talk about the Kashmir itself, how that issue has evolved through the years

02:15:31.860 --> 02:15:34.860
[Amit Varma]: and all the politics and geopolitics about that.

02:15:34.860 --> 02:15:40.240
[Amit Varma]: Let's look at the 370 within the context of the fact that this was one of the key demands

02:15:40.240 --> 02:15:44.020
[Amit Varma]: of a resurgent Hindu right, which is now on the political ascendant.

02:15:44.020 --> 02:15:49.260
[Amit Varma]: Some would say it's a coming together of culture and politics in a sense.

02:15:49.260 --> 02:15:53.980
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, their key demands were things like cow slaughter, 370, these have been the

02:15:53.980 --> 02:15:56.700
[Amit Varma]: signature issues which they've used through the years.

02:15:56.700 --> 02:16:01.100
[Amit Varma]: And you now see all of these playing out in a in on a bigger scale where cow slaughter

02:16:01.100 --> 02:16:04.140
[Amit Varma]: is again an issue, you have lynchings going up in the country.

02:16:04.140 --> 02:16:08.500
[Amit Varma]: Now they've done 370, maybe they'll build the temple next, who knows?

02:16:08.500 --> 02:16:12.340
[Amit Varma]: What direction do you see this country broadly going in?

02:16:12.340 --> 02:16:17.780
[Amit Varma]: And this is again, you know, outside the issue of Kashmir, because like I said, I think what

02:16:17.780 --> 02:16:21.660
[Amit Varma]: happened on August 5th is more than just about Kashmir is also about India.

02:16:21.660 --> 02:16:24.620
[Guest]: Yeah, you know, historians make a very bad astrologers.

02:16:24.620 --> 02:16:28.340
[Amit Varma]: So you know, I have no means of dividing where we are going down.

02:16:28.340 --> 02:16:31.620
[Amit Varma]: What's the best case scenario and worst case scenario for the next 10 years?

02:16:31.620 --> 02:16:35.100
[Guest]: You know, honestly, I, I don't think I'm very well placed to answer that question.

02:16:35.100 --> 02:16:38.740
[Guest]: But let me take a stab at giving a serious answer to your first question.

02:16:38.740 --> 02:16:43.820
[Guest]: Now, you're right that, you know, we are at a in a different kind of a political situation

02:16:43.820 --> 02:16:48.740
[Guest]: where there is a new political party, which has emerged as the hegemonic force by hegemonic

02:16:48.740 --> 02:16:53.740
[Guest]: as a force, which has the consent of a large number of electorate.

02:16:53.740 --> 02:16:57.700
[Guest]: And especially if you look at the last election in the Hindi speaking states, the BJP has

02:16:57.700 --> 02:17:00.100
[Guest]: clearly emerged as a hegemonic power.

02:17:00.100 --> 02:17:03.460
[Guest]: And they believe that these are issues on which they have campaigned.

02:17:03.460 --> 02:17:07.020
[Guest]: And again, they're right in saying so, and that they have a mandate, therefore, to do

02:17:07.020 --> 02:17:08.020
[Guest]: it.

02:17:08.020 --> 02:17:10.580
[Guest]: And that is clearly sort of understandable, it is legitimate.

02:17:10.580 --> 02:17:16.100
[Guest]: But as we know, with any liberal democracy of the kind that we are, the things like the

02:17:16.100 --> 02:17:21.140
[Guest]: Constitution exists for a certain reason, which is basically to sort of ensure that

02:17:21.140 --> 02:17:24.820
[Guest]: democratic majoritarianism cannot upturn the fundamentals of the state.

02:17:24.820 --> 02:17:29.340
[Guest]: That is what the Constitution's, you know, so called, you know, function is.

02:17:29.340 --> 02:17:35.860
[Guest]: Now, if, if we are going to overturn the procedural norms of using the Constitution for various

02:17:35.860 --> 02:17:41.580
[Guest]: ends, simply because of claiming majoritarian legitimation, then I think we are at an inflection

02:17:41.580 --> 02:17:42.580
[Guest]: point.

02:17:42.580 --> 02:17:45.580
[Guest]: We have been in a similar inflection point in the past, there used to be huge tussles

02:17:45.580 --> 02:17:50.300
[Guest]: between what the state could do, the government could do vis-a-vis the Constitution back in

02:17:50.300 --> 02:17:53.820
[Guest]: the Indira Gandhi period, which has then led to this doctrine of the basic structure, which

02:17:53.820 --> 02:17:57.100
[Guest]: came out of the Keshavand Bharti sort of, you know, case.

02:17:57.100 --> 02:18:03.020
[Guest]: Now, the question for us is whether now we are doing things where another more clever

02:18:03.020 --> 02:18:08.020
[Guest]: way of using the provisions of the Constitution to do these kinds of things is possible, and

02:18:08.020 --> 02:18:11.260
[Guest]: whether the courts are actually going to uphold, which is why I think it is going to be interesting

02:18:11.260 --> 02:18:15.160
[Guest]: to see how the courts deal with these legal challenges.

02:18:15.160 --> 02:18:18.640
[Guest]: Because the courts do not sit in the heaven, they sit in this country.

02:18:18.640 --> 02:18:22.380
[Guest]: And they have to also take into account various other kinds of factors as they do it.

02:18:22.380 --> 02:18:23.380
[Guest]: Like public opinion?

02:18:23.380 --> 02:18:24.380
[Guest]: I don't know whether they do.

02:18:24.380 --> 02:18:25.720
[Guest]: I'm not a constitutional scholar.

02:18:25.720 --> 02:18:29.700
[Guest]: But I would imagine that in the past, if you look at it, I mean, courts have always not

02:18:29.700 --> 02:18:33.940
[Guest]: necessarily taken on the executive in a very direct way when it comes to this thing.

02:18:33.940 --> 02:18:39.300
[Guest]: But I think what has happened in this month will raise a series of legal questions, which

02:18:39.300 --> 02:18:44.180
[Guest]: are at least of as much importance as the sort of landmark cases in the Supreme Court

02:18:44.180 --> 02:18:47.780
[Guest]: starting in the late 60s running through to the mid 70s happened.

02:18:47.780 --> 02:18:52.540
[Guest]: And as I see it, you know, there is a tussle always in any country between democracy and

02:18:52.540 --> 02:18:53.540
[Guest]: constitutionalism, right?

02:18:53.540 --> 02:18:57.020
[Guest]: I mean, these are not necessarily compatible values, right?

02:18:57.020 --> 02:19:02.140
[Guest]: And we have to see how this judgment plays out, in a sense, how this balance, what kind

02:19:02.140 --> 02:19:03.460
[Guest]: of new equilibrium do we arrive at?

02:19:03.460 --> 02:19:07.300
[Guest]: If we are going to arrive at an equilibrium that listen, majoritarian legitimization is

02:19:07.300 --> 02:19:11.780
[Guest]: sufficient to override all other kinds of things, and everything is up for grabs, then

02:19:11.780 --> 02:19:15.140
[Guest]: possibly we are looking at a very, very different way of doing things.

02:19:15.140 --> 02:19:18.580
[Guest]: In the past, again, this is not the first time that we are in a situation like this.

02:19:18.580 --> 02:19:21.660
[Guest]: Mrs. Gandhi attempted many such things during the emergency.

02:19:21.660 --> 02:19:26.100
[Guest]: But post the emergency, many of those things were also repealed, right?

02:19:26.100 --> 02:19:28.820
[Guest]: We saw many of those constitutional amendments sort of being repealed, and so on.

02:19:28.820 --> 02:19:31.500
[Guest]: Now, I'm not trying to suggest that we are in any comparable situation.

02:19:31.500 --> 02:19:36.580
[Guest]: But all I'm trying to say is that the questions are similar, which is about how do we go about

02:19:36.580 --> 02:19:38.380
[Guest]: using the provisions of the Constitution?

02:19:38.380 --> 02:19:43.500
[Guest]: What is the relationship between a majoritarian affirmation in elections, and the kinds of

02:19:43.500 --> 02:19:45.500
[Guest]: constitutional changes that we can bring about?

02:19:45.500 --> 02:19:47.660
[Guest]: And what does this mean for the country as a whole?

02:19:47.660 --> 02:19:51.660
[Amit Varma]: And also just to sort of take that thought forward and throw this at you at the same

02:19:51.660 --> 02:19:57.660
[Amit Varma]: time is that one fundamental way in which this tussle, as you use the term currently,

02:19:57.660 --> 02:20:02.900
[Amit Varma]: is different from what Indira Gandhi did was Indira Gandhi was, as far as I can see, driven

02:20:02.900 --> 02:20:05.380
[Amit Varma]: essentially by the will to power.

02:20:05.380 --> 02:20:09.700
[Amit Varma]: And whatever changes in the Constitution she made was driven by that.

02:20:09.700 --> 02:20:14.980
[Amit Varma]: But there is a deeper philosophical dispute here in the legitimacy of this Constitution

02:20:14.980 --> 02:20:21.300
[Amit Varma]: and the kind of constitutionalism that we have, where a lot of Hindutva right wing thinkers

02:20:21.300 --> 02:20:26.460
[Amit Varma]: have, for example, argued in the past that this is a constitution made by liberal elites

02:20:26.460 --> 02:20:31.580
[Amit Varma]: and doesn't represent what the people actually believe in or stand for.

02:20:31.580 --> 02:20:36.180
[Amit Varma]: So when you talk about, for example, you use the phrases democratic majoritarianism shaking

02:20:36.180 --> 02:20:40.580
[Amit Varma]: the foundations of the state, I think what the argument from the Hindu right would be

02:20:40.580 --> 02:20:45.940
[Amit Varma]: that the foundations of the state are the wrong foundations, that they don't agree with

02:20:45.940 --> 02:20:49.660
[Amit Varma]: the definition of constitutionalism that you and I would agree with that it's essentially

02:20:49.660 --> 02:20:52.980
[Amit Varma]: the Constitution has to be a check on the power of the state and has to protect the

02:20:52.980 --> 02:20:56.860
[Amit Varma]: people against the state, but they would not necessarily agree with that.

02:20:56.860 --> 02:21:02.220
[Amit Varma]: And in that tussle, who is to say that whether their vision of what the Constitution should

02:21:02.220 --> 02:21:07.860
[Amit Varma]: be is more legitimate, or our vision, which is still the vision of liberal elites?

02:21:07.860 --> 02:21:14.460
[Guest]: No, I agree with you that there is no reason to assume that, you know, a group of people,

02:21:14.460 --> 02:21:17.260
[Guest]: maybe a majority of people in this country may have a very different vision of what the

02:21:17.260 --> 02:21:18.260
[Guest]: Constitution should be.

02:21:18.260 --> 02:21:23.380
[Guest]: But all I'm trying to say is that, if you want to reach that vision, you cannot do it

02:21:23.380 --> 02:21:26.900
[Guest]: through the existing constitutional means, you need to convene another Constituent Assembly

02:21:26.900 --> 02:21:28.100
[Guest]: and do it.

02:21:28.100 --> 02:21:30.820
[Guest]: That is how you can supersede the existing Constitution, because the existing Constitution

02:21:30.820 --> 02:21:36.220
[Guest]: lays certain kinds of provisions in here, including the doctrine of basic structure,

02:21:36.220 --> 02:21:40.180
[Guest]: which has now become I think, again, I'm not a constitutional scholar, but as a historian,

02:21:40.180 --> 02:21:44.540
[Guest]: to the extent that I've read and understood these things, it has become a fairly well

02:21:44.540 --> 02:21:48.300
[Guest]: defined doctrine, which is actually applicable in many, used in many other countries as well,

02:21:48.300 --> 02:21:50.260
[Guest]: in dealing with these situations, right.

02:21:50.260 --> 02:21:54.420
[Guest]: And in a sense, should also incidentally be applicable to the Constitution of the JNK

02:21:54.420 --> 02:21:58.300
[Guest]: state itself, who's not only basic structure, but entire structure has been evacuated.

02:21:58.300 --> 02:21:59.300
[Guest]: Exactly.

02:21:59.300 --> 02:22:03.180
[Guest]: So, that's why I'm saying that there are many interesting and important constitutional questions

02:22:03.180 --> 02:22:07.020
[Guest]: at stake here, which will be discussed and the courts will come to some kind of a judgment

02:22:07.020 --> 02:22:08.580
[Guest]: on these questions.

02:22:08.580 --> 02:22:13.260
[Guest]: So, I do not for once deny that people may want to have a different Constitution.

02:22:13.260 --> 02:22:18.180
[Guest]: All I'm trying to say is that we are in a currently in one constitutional regime.

02:22:18.180 --> 02:22:21.020
[Guest]: You may feel that, listen, this constitutional regime is the wrong one for this country to

02:22:21.020 --> 02:22:22.020
[Guest]: have.

02:22:22.020 --> 02:22:27.540
[Guest]: Though I, I'm hard pressed to say that it is done by some bunch of liberal elites alone,

02:22:27.540 --> 02:22:28.540
[Guest]: right?

02:22:28.540 --> 02:22:33.940
[Guest]: I think that is not the case to all of us, especially our readers, you know, our listeners,

02:22:33.940 --> 02:22:39.180
[Guest]: I would recommend a book by Rohit Dey, which is about the people's constitution, about

02:22:39.180 --> 02:22:43.860
[Guest]: how very ordinary people in India, as soon as the Constitution came into effect, use

02:22:43.860 --> 02:22:47.180
[Guest]: the provisions of the Constitution to secure their own rights, to suggest that this is

02:22:47.180 --> 02:22:51.700
[Guest]: a document of by and for liberal elites is I think, a travesty of history.

02:22:51.700 --> 02:22:53.460
[Amit Varma]: I'll get that book from the show notes.

02:22:53.460 --> 02:22:54.460
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:22:54.460 --> 02:22:56.060
[Guest]: So, I may have got the title of the book.

02:22:56.060 --> 02:22:58.180
[Guest]: I think that's what it's called the people's constitution.

02:22:58.180 --> 02:22:59.260
[Guest]: I think it's a very important book.

02:22:59.260 --> 02:23:03.980
[Guest]: I think it's one of the most important books written about the history of the Indian constitution

02:23:03.980 --> 02:23:05.860
[Guest]: making process and what it meant.

02:23:05.860 --> 02:23:11.380
[Guest]: And I think it fundamentally belies this proposition that it was a document for liberal elites

02:23:11.380 --> 02:23:12.860
[Guest]: and made by liberal elites.

02:23:12.860 --> 02:23:19.140
[Guest]: I freely concede that it was a, you know, a constitution, which kind of was made on

02:23:19.140 --> 02:23:20.740
[Guest]: limited franchise and so on.

02:23:20.740 --> 02:23:24.260
[Guest]: But to suggest therefore that it is ipso facto illegitimate or that it is under representative

02:23:24.260 --> 02:23:26.820
[Guest]: of this country, I think is a travesty.

02:23:26.820 --> 02:23:28.500
[Guest]: I don't think that is true.

02:23:28.500 --> 02:23:32.780
[Guest]: Of course, the, you know, any group of people who believe that they have the numbers and

02:23:32.780 --> 02:23:37.020
[Guest]: the political power to want to bring about a new constitutional regime are entirely at

02:23:37.020 --> 02:23:38.460
[Guest]: liberty to do so.

02:23:38.460 --> 02:23:42.700
[Guest]: But it cannot be done within the frameworks and contours of the existing system.

02:23:42.700 --> 02:23:47.540
[Guest]: You need to have a total revolution, approve all of this stuff and take us to a totally

02:23:47.540 --> 02:23:48.540
[Guest]: different one.

02:23:48.540 --> 02:23:52.600
[Guest]: I'd imagine, you know, that is an enterprise about which a lot of people will have some

02:23:52.600 --> 02:23:53.600
[Guest]: questions to ask.

02:23:53.600 --> 02:23:57.300
[Amit Varma]: I can't make out if that's a hopeful note to end on or not.

02:23:57.300 --> 02:24:01.700
